 television series, which premiered on April 2, 2020 on [[Tokyo MX]], [[Nippon BS Broadcasting|BS11]], and [[AT-X (company)|AT-X]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-03-06/hachinantte-sore-wa-inai-desho-fantasy-anime-ad-reveals-2020-airing/.144230|title=Hachinantte Sore wa Inai Desh\u014d! Fantasy Anime's Ad Reveals 2020 Airing|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=March 6, 2019|accessdate=March 6, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"April\"/> The series is co-animated by [[Shin-Ei Animation]] and [[SynergySP]], with Tatsuo Miura directing the series, Takeshi Miyamoto handling series composition and Keiji Tanabe designing the characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-07-07/the-8th-son-are-you-kidding-me-tv-anime-promo-video-visual-revealed/.148737|title='The 8th son? Are you kidding me?' TV Anime's Promo Video, Visual Revealed (Updated)|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 7, 2019|accessdate=July 7, 2019}}</ref> Minako Sato is composing the series' music.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-01-18/the-8th-son-are-you-kidding-me-tv-anime-1st-promo-video-previews-cast-voices/.155511|title='The 8th son? Are you kidding me?' TV Anime's 1st Promo Video Previews Cast Voices|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=January 18, 2020|accessdate=January 18, 2020}}</ref> The opening theme is {{nihongo|Space-Time of the Hesitant Person|\u6642\u7a7a\u306e\u8ff7\u3044\u4eba|\"Jik\u016b no Mayoi Hito\"}} performed by Demon Kakka and Arika Takarano, while the ending theme is {{nihongo|Moonlight Monologue|\u6708\u660e\u308a\u306eMonologue|\"Tsukiakari Monologue\"}} performed by Akino Arai x AKINO from Bless4.<ref name=\"April\">{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-02-28/the-8th-son-are-you-kidding-me-anime-2nd-promo-video-reveals-previews-theme-songs/.156944|title='The 8th Son? Are You Kidding Me?' Anime's 2nd Promo Video Reveals, Previews Theme Songs|publisher=Anime News Network|date=February 28, 2020|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref> [[Crunchyroll]] will be streaming the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-02-15/crunchyroll-to-stream-the-8th-son-are-you-kidding-me-my-next-life-as-a-villainess-that-time-i-got-reincarnated-as-a-slime-season-2-so-im-a-spider-so-what-anime/.156492|title=Crunchyroll to Stream 'The 8th Son? Are You Kidding Me?,' My Next Life As a Villainess, That Time I Got Reincarnated as a Slime Season 2, 'So I'm a Spider, So What?' Anime|publisher=Anime News Network|date=February 15, 2020|accessdate=February 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"plainrowheaders wikitable\" style=\"width:98%; margin:auto; background:#FFF;\"\n|- style=\"border-bottom: 3px solid #CCF;\"\n!{{Abbr|No.|Number}}\n! Title<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hachinan-anime.com/story/|title=STORY / TV\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u300c\u516b\u7537\u3063\u3066\u3001\u305d\u308c\u306f\u306a\u3044\u3067\u3057\u3087\u3046\uff01\u300d\u516c\u5f0f\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8|accessdate=April 3, 2020|language=Japanese}}</ref>{{efn|All English titles are taken from [[Crunchyroll]].}}\n!Original air date\n|-\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber       = 1\n| Title               = The 8th Son? Are You Kidding Me?\n| TranslitTitle       = Hachi-nan tte, Sore wa Nai Desh\u014d!\n| NativeTitle         = \u516b\u7537\u3063\u3066\u3001\u305d\u308c\u306f\u306a\u3044\u3067\u3057\u3087\u3046\uff01\n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate     = {{Start date|2020|4|2}}\n| ShortSummary        = A Japanese salaryman falls asleep before waking up and finding himself as a five year old boy named Wendelin von Benno Baumeister, during the wedding of his oldest brother Kurt and his wife Amalie. Despite being nobles, Wendelin discovers the Baumeisters are poor and only owns small farmlands which most of it will be inherit by Kurt while the rest of his six older brothers have either married into another family, finding work as a government official or soldier, leaving him nothing to inherit. Wendelin later discovers he has the ability to use magic. While searching for firewood for his family, Wendelin meets Alfred Rainford, who detected the boy's magic, saving him from a wild boar and vows to teach him how to use magic.\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber       = 2\n| Title               = A Succession Dispute? Are You Kidding Me?\n| TranslitTitle       = Oie s\u014dd\u014d tte, Sore wa Nai Desh\u014d!\n| NativeTitle         = \u304a\u5bb6\u9a12\u52d5\u3063\u3066\u3001\u305d\u308c\u306f\u306a\u3044\u3067\u3057\u3087\u3046\uff01\n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate     = {{Start date|2020|4|9}}\n| ShortSummary        = Wendelin decides to keep his magic a secret after learning it moves him ahead of Kurt in the line of family inheritance, risking assassination attempts from Kurt. Alfred discovers Wendelin has an extraordinarily high magic capacity. Alfred displays several unusual symptoms, cold skin, no sense of taste and bouts of physical pain. Wendelin\u2019s strange behaviour draws Kurt\u2019s attention. Wendelin decides he wants to be an adventurer instead of a lord, making Kurt less suspicious, but Adventurers Academy is expensive, so Wendelin decides to work to pay his own tuition. To help with travelling Alfred teaches Wendelin flight magic. Wendelin\u2019s father hears a rumour of a Whispering Dead nearby, a sentient corpse doomed to become a mindless zombie. Wendelin realises he means Alfred and confronts him. Alfred admits he is dead but came back as a Whispering Dead to pass on his knowledge to an apprentice. Having done so, he teaches Wendelin holy magic to purge him and let him pass to the afterlife. Years later Wendelin leaves his family to become an adventurer. \n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber       = 3\n| Title               = A Loner? Are You Kidding Me?\n| TranslitTitle       = Bocchi tte, Sore wa Nai Desh\u014d!\n| NativeTitle         = \u30dc\u30c3\u30c1\u3063\u3066\u3001\u305d\u308c\u306f\u306a\u3044\u3067\u3057\u3087\u3046\uff01\n| NativeTitleLangCode = ja\n| OriginalAirDate     = {{Start date|2020|4|16}}\n| ShortSummary        = Wendelin attends the Adventurers Academy and wants to make friends so they can form a party but due to his lack of communications skills and high level of magic, he causes a misunderstanding with the rest of the students who mistakenly believe they are not skilled enough to join Wendelin's party. Meanwhile, three students, Erwin, Louise and Iina, shared a bond over being in the lower class and the youngest children of their families. Wanting to gain Wendelin's recognition, the three attempt to hunt large pack of wolves but are overwhelmed by their numbers until Wendelin rescues them. Due to a misunderstanding, the three believes Wendelin sees them as a burden when in reality he wants to be friends with them. The students later attend a party hosted by Duke Braihiraider who takes an interests with Wendelin as the latter's father is a vassal of Braihiraider. When the Duke asks for a private meeting with Wendelin, he asks Erwin, Louise and Iina to join him much to their surprise. Wendelin and the others learn Braihiraider brought them to meet his court wizard, Brantack Lyngstad, Alfred's former teacher, who confirms his suspicions that Alfred passed on his knowledge to Wendelin before his passing. Realising that Wendelin is not so different to them, Erwin, Louise and Iina agree to be Wendelin's friends and join his party. As a reward for returning Alfred's possessions in his magic bag to Braihiraider, Wendelin is rewarded a thousand gold coins and inherits Alfred's estate much to everyone's surprise.\n}}\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://ncode.syosetu.com/n8802bq/|Web novel}} at [[Sh\u014dsetsuka ni Nar\u014d]] {{in lang|ja}}\n* {{Official website|http://mfbooks.jp/books/series/hachinan/|Light novel official website}} {{in lang|ja}}\n* {{Official website|http://hachinan-anime.com/|Anime official website}} {{in lang|ja}}\n* {{ann|light novel|22284}}\n\n{{Shin-Ei Animation}}\n{{SynergySP}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:8th Son? Are You Kidding Me?}}\n[[Category:2014 Japanese novels]]\n[[Category:Anime and manga based on light novels]]\n[[Category:Fantasy anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Harem_anime_and_manga]]\n[[Category:Isekai anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Japanese webcomics]]\n[[Category:Kadokawa Shoten manga]]\n[[Category:Kadokawa Dwango franchises]]\n[[Category:Light novels]]\n[[Category:Light novels first published online]]\n[[Category:Seinen manga]]\n[[Category:Shin-Ei Animation]]\n[[Category:Sh\u014dsetsuka ni Nar\u014d]]\n[[Category:Webcomics in print]]\n\n{{anime-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Tasaar", "label": "safe", "comment": "feel asleep -> fell asleep", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_8th_Son%3F_Are_You_Kidding_Me%3F"}
{"title_page": "Defence Inspectorate (Namibia)", "text_new": "{{Copy edit|for=Please fix box at bottom so references aren\u2019t included |date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = Defence Inspectorate Directorate\n| image = \n| caption = \n| dates = \n| country = [[Namibia]]\n| allegiance =\n| branch =\n| type = \n| role = \n| size = \n| command_structure = [[Namibia Defence Force]]\n| garrison = \n| garrison_label = \n| nickname = \n| colors = \n| colors_label = \n| march = \n| start_date = \n| engagements = \n| current_commander = [[Brigadier General]] Fiina Amupolo\n| current_commander_label = Chief of Staff\n| ceremonial_chief = \n| ceremonial_chief_label = <!-- Insignia -->\n}}\n\n\nThe '''Defence Inspectorate''' Directorate is the branch of the [[Namibian Defence Force]] responsible for maintaining efficiency and effectiveness of the force. Its main role is to issue corrective measures when shortfalls are detected<ref name=\"Ainima 18\">{{cite journal |last=Ainima|first=B |title=Establishment of Namibian Defence Force Inspectorate |journal=NDF Journal |volume=44 |date=June 2011|page=18}}</ref>.\n\n==Organisation==\nDefence Inspectorate Directorate consists of three divisions:\n\n===Defence Capabilities Division===\nIt is mandated to capability, Policy oversight and conducting support systems evaluation.\n\n===Internal Audit Division===\nIt is mandated to conduct forensic and [[Information Technology]] audits, Financial Risk management. The division also carries out Materiel Resources Inspection.\n\n===Complaints Division=== \nIt is mandated to investigating complaints,both internal and external.\n\n==Leadership==\n{{Post-start|caption=Defence Inspector General|float=}}\n{{Post-header|post-name=Chief of Staff}}\n{{Post-member|from-date=19 July 2011|post-incumbent=Brigadier General Philipus Shikuma Kamati<ref name=\"Tomas 4\">{{cite journal |last=Ministry of Defence|first=M |title=Inauguration of 21 Inf Bde Commander |journal=NDF Journal |volume=41 |date=September 2011|page=4}}</ref>||to-date=unknown date}}\n{{Post-member|from-date=1990 date|post-incumbent=Brigadier General Solomon Shilongo||to-date=2016}}\n{{Post-member|from-date=10 January 2019|post-incumbent=Brigadier General Fiina Amupolo<ref>{{cite web |title=Promotion 2019 - GRN Portal |url=http://www.mod.gov.na/promotion-2019 |website=www.mod.gov.na |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>||to-date=Incumbent}}\n{{Post-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Military of Namibia]]\n\n\n{{Namibia-gov-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Copy edit|for=Please fix box at bottom so references aren\u2019t included |date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = Defence Inspectorate Directorate\n| image = \n| caption = \n| dates = \n| country = [[Namibia]]\n| allegiance =\n| branch =\n| type = \n| role = \n| size = \n| command_structure = [[Namibia Defence Force]]\n| garrison = \n| garrison_label = \n| nickname = \n| colors = \n| colors_label = \n| march = \n| start_date = \n| engagements = \n| current_commander = [[Brigadier General]] Fiina Amupolo\n| current_commander_label = Chief of Staff\n| ceremonial_chief = \n| ceremonial_chief_label = <!-- Insignia -->\n}}\n\n\nThe '''Defence Inspectorate''' Directorate is the branch of the [[Namibian Defence Force]] responsible for maintaining efficiency and effectiveness of the force. Its main role is to issue corrective measures when shortfalls are detected<ref name=\"Ainima 18\">{{cite journal |last=Ainima|first=B |title=Establishment of Namibian Defence Force Inspectorate |journal=NDF Journal |volume=44 |date=June 2011|page=18}}</ref>.\n\n==Organisation==\nDefence Inspectorate Directorate is consisting of three divisions:\n\n===Defence Capabilities Division===\nIt is mandated to capability, Policy oversight and conducting support systems evaluation.\n\n===Internal Audit Division===\nIt is mandated to conduct forensic and [[Information Technology]] audits, Financial Risk management. The division also carries out Materiel Resources Inspection.\n\n===Complaints Division=== \nIt is mandated to investigating complaints,both internal and external.\n\n==Leadership==\n{{Post-start|caption=Defence Inspector General|float=}}\n{{Post-header|post-name=Chief of Staff}}\n{{Post-member|from-date=19 July 2011|post-incumbent=Brigadier General Philipus Shikuma Kamati<ref name=\"Tomas 4\">{{cite journal |last=Ministry of Defence|first=M |title=Inauguration of 21 Inf Bde Commander |journal=NDF Journal |volume=41 |date=September 2011|page=4}}</ref>||to-date=unknown date}}\n{{Post-member|from-date=1990 date|post-incumbent=Brigadier General Solomon Shilongo||to-date=2016}}\n{{Post-member|from-date=10 January 2019|post-incumbent=Brigadier General Fiina Amupolo<ref>{{cite web |title=Promotion 2019 - GRN Portal |url=http://www.mod.gov.na/promotion-2019 |website=www.mod.gov.na |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>||to-date=Incumbent}}\n{{Post-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Military of Namibia]]\n\n\n{{Namibia-gov-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Charmanderblue", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOrganisation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Defence_Inspectorate_(Namibia)"}
{"title_page": "Ren\u00e9 Higuita", "text_new": "{{short description|Colombian footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Ren\u00e9 Higuita\n| image = Ren\u00e9 Higuita, 2007.jpg\n| caption= Higuita in 2007\n| fullname = Jos\u00e9 Ren\u00e9 Higuita Zapata\n| height = 1.75 m<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/rene-higuita/|title=Ren\u00e9 Higuita|website=worldfootball.net|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1966|8|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Medell\u00edn]], Colombia\n| currentclub = [[Atl\u00e9tico Nacional]] (goalkeeper coach)\n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[Millonarios FC|Millonarios]]\n| years1 = 1985\n| clubs1 = [[Millonarios FC|Millonarios]]\n| caps1 = 16\n| goals1 = 7\n| years2 = 1986\u20131992\n| clubs2 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Nacional]]\n| caps2 = 112\n| goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 1992\n| clubs3 = [[Real Valladolid]]\n| caps3 = 15\n| goals3 = 2\n| years4 = 1993\u20131997\n| clubs4 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Nacional]]\n| caps4 = 69\n| goals4 = 1\n| years5 = 1997\u20131998\n| clubs5 = [[Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz|Veracruz]]\n| caps5 = 30\n| goals5 = 2\n| years6 = 1999\u20132000\n| clubs6 = [[Independiente Medell\u00edn]]\n| caps6 = 20\n| goals6 = 11\n| years7 = 2000\u20132001\n| clubs7 = [[Real Cartagena]]\n| caps7 = 21\n| goals7 = 0\n| years8 = 2001\u20132002\n| clubs8 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Junior]]\n| caps8 = 4\n| goals8 = 0\n| years9 = 2002\u20132003\n| clubs9 = [[Deportivo Pereira]]\n| caps9 = 13\n| goals9 = 0\n| years10 = 2004\n| clubs10 = [[Sociedad Deportiva Aucas|Aucas]]\n| caps10 = 35\n| goals10 = 3\n| years11 = 2005\n| clubs11 = \n| caps11 = 13\n| goals11 = 1\n| years12 = 2007\n| clubs12 = [[Guaros F\u00fatbol Club|Guaros FC]]\n| caps12 = 10\n| goals12 = 5\n| years13 = 2008\n| clubs13 = [[Leones F. C.|Deportivo Rionegro]]\n| caps13 = 10\n| goals13 = 3\n| years14 = 2008\u20132009\n| clubs14 = [[Deportivo Pereira]]\n| caps14 = 12\n| goals14 = 5\n| totalcaps = 380\n| totalgoals = 41\n| nationalyears1 = 1987\u20131999\n| nationalteam1 = [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]]<ref name=\"International caps and goals\">{{cite web|title=RSSSF|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/higuita-intl.html}}</ref>\n| nationalcaps1 = 68\n| nationalgoals1 = 3\n}}\n{{spanish name 2|Higuita|Zapata}}\n'''Jos\u00e9 Ren\u00e9 Higuita Zapata''' ({{IPA-es|re\u02c8ne i\u02c8\u0263ita}}; born 27 August 1966) is a Colombian former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]]. He was nicknamed ''El Loco'' (\"The Madman\") for his high-risk '[[Goalkeeper (association football)#Sweeper-keeper|sweeper-keeper]]' playing style and his flair for the dramatic.\n\nHiguita's style of play, which was first shown to a global audience during the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]], was pioneering in influencing goalkeepers to take more responsibility for situations further from the goal.<ref name=\"The Legacy of Rene Higuita\">Tim Vickery (10 February 2010). [https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/legacy/timvickery/2010/02/the_legacy_of_rene_higuita.html \"The Legacy of Rene Higuita\"]. BBC. Retrieved 11 June 2014</ref> \n\n[[IFFHS]] ranked Higuita the 8th best keeper in South American in history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/player/rene-higuita|title=Rene Higuita Biography, Career Info, Records & Achievements|website=www.sportskeeda.com|language=en|access-date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe is also ranked as one of the 10 highest-scoring goalkeepers in history, with 41 goals overall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1842588-the-10-best-goalscoring-goalkeepers|title=The 10 Best Goalscoring Goalkeepers|last=Bailey|first=Ryan|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHiguita was born in [[Medell\u00edn]], [[Antioquia Department|Antioquia]] to a single mother, Maria Dioselina. His mother died when he was very young, so his grandma had to take care of him. He was very poor as a child, so he had to work as newspaper mailman and many other jobs in order to survive.\n\n==Club career==\nHiguita started his playing career with [[Millonarios F.C.|Millonarios]] and transferred to [[Atl\u00e9tico Nacional]] in 1986. He played the majority of his club career with the Colombian side where he helped the team win the [[Categor\u00eda Primera A|Colombian League]] on numerous occasions as well as the [[Copa Libertadores]] and [[Copa Interamericana]], both in 1989. After leaving them, he moved to Spain to play with [[Real Valladolid]] for one season, before coming back to Atletico Nacional for four years. He then left to Mexico to play for [[Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz|Veracruz]] before coming back to the Colombian league to play for Atletico's city rivals, [[Independiente Medell\u00edn]].\n\nHe briefly retired in 2005 after failing a drug test while playing for [[Aucas Quito|Aucas]].\n\nHe came out of retirement on 21 July 2007 to sign for Venezuelan club [[Guaros F\u00fatbol Club|Guaros FC]]. In January 2008, aged 41, he signed for the Colombian second division team [[Leones F.C.|Deportivo Rionegro]]. In June 2008 he signed for another Colombia team, [[Deportivo Pereira]], and finally retired on 25 January 2010.<ref>{{cite web|author=Tim Vickery |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/timvickery/2010/02/the_legacy_of_rene_higuita.html |title=The legacy of Rene Higuita |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=30 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Higuita pateando.jpg|thumb|150px|Higuita in the training sessions with Colombia during the 1990 World Cup]]\nHiguita's first major tournament was the [[1989 Copa Am\u00e9rica]], where the team was knocked out in the first round. In the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]], he played an important part to lead the country into the round of 16 for the first time ever. However, Higuita's unorthodox playing style caused a mistake by him that knocked Colombia out of the World Cup, when he tried to feint [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]] striker [[Roger Milla]] but failed, and Milla dispossessed him and scored, which put Cameroon through to the quarter-finals. Higuita described it as \"a mistake as big as a house\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-fa-cup---schmeichel-slices-into-fixture-jam-1145084.html|title=Schmeichel slices into fixture|last=Shaw|first=Phil|date=16 February 1998|work=The Independent}}</ref> As a result of such behaviour, Higuita was nicknamed ''El Loco'' (\"The Madman\").<ref name=\"scorpion kick keeper\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-12792304|title=Colombia 'scorpion kick' keeper Higuita runs for mayor|date=19 March 2011|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nHe played in the [[1991 Copa Am\u00e9rica]] where the team finished fourth. His last call up for the national team was for the [[1999 Copa Am\u00e9rica]].\n\nHiguita often took set-pieces for the [[Colombia national football team|Colombian national team]], in all, he scored three goals in his 68 international appearances.\n\n==Style of play==\nOn the pitch, Higuita was known for his dramatic flair, composure under pressure, and eccentric playing style, often taking unnecessary risks and actively coming out of his area to anticipate opponents, play the ball out to defenders, undertake individual dribbling runs, and attempt to score goals, which led him to be described as a '[[sweeper-keeper]]'; he was therefore a pioneer in influencing other goalkeepers to take more responsibility for situations further away from the goal.<ref name=\"The Legacy of Rene Higuita\"/> Although he was a goalkeeper, Higuita also became known for scoring directly from [[Direct free kick|free-kicks]], as well as [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalties]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/33006305|title=Rogerio Ceni: Sao Paulo keeper into club record books|publisher=BBC|date=4 June 2015|accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nHis style of play led to the creation of the [[Back-pass rule]], which is also known as the ''Higuita Law.''\n\n[[IFFHS]] ranked Higuita the 8th best keeper in South American history. \n\nHiguita's style of play, which was first shown to a global audience during the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]], was pioneering in influencing goalkeepers to take more responsibility for situations further from the goal.\n\n====Scorpion Kick====\nFurthermore, Higuita reportedly invented the [[scorpion kick]], a movement which involves the player jumping forward, positioning their legs over their head, and in doing so, kicks the ball away with their heels; one of Higuita's most notable uses of the scorpion was when he performed it while clearing a cross from [[Jamie Redknapp]] during a friendly against [[England national football team|England]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] on 6 September 1995, earning him considerable media attention.<ref name=\"scorpion kick keeper\" /> It ranked 94th in [[Channel 4]]'s ''[[100 Greatest Sporting Moments]]'' in 2002.<ref name=\"UK poll\">[http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/G/greatest_sporting/results.html 100 Greatest sporting moments \u2013 results] ''[[Channel 4]]''. Retrieved 28 August 2014</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nHiguita has expressed the wish to coach the Colombian national team and in December 2008 he got the job of goalkeeper coach for his former club [[Real Valladolid]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://elvalladolid.com/articles/8531-rene-higuita-nuevo-preparador-de-porteros |title=Ren\u00e9 Higuita, nuevo preparador de porteros en |publisher=Elvalladolid.com |accessdate=30 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090917201325/http://elvalladolid.com/articles/8531-rene-higuita-nuevo-preparador-de-porteros |archivedate=17 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nHe joined [[Al Nassr FC]] in Saudi Arabia in 2011, and was the club goalkeeper coach for about 5 years, until 2016. \n\nHe rejoined Atletico Nacional on 28 June 2017 after receiving a coaching job as the goalkeeping coach. Upon rejoining, he said \"the dream of my life was to return to Atletico Nacional\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/football/other-football/scorpion-kick-goalkeeper-higuita-joins-atletico-nacional/article19163654.ece|title=Scorpion kick goalkeeper Higuita joins Atletico Nacional|last=Lines|first=Oliver|website=Sportstar|language=en|access-date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHiguita is married to Magnolia, with whom he has three children, Andr\u00e9s, Pamela and Wilfred. He also has a daughter, Cindy Carolina, from a previous marriage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?q=rene+higuita+children&rlz=1C1ZKTG_enUS831US832&oq=rene+higuita+children&aqs=chrome..69i57.3921j0j4&sourceid=chrome&ie=UTF-8|title=rene higuita children - Google Search|website=www.google.com|access-date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe is friends with [[Diego Maradona]] and played in the Argentine's farewell match in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/argentina-cries-for-that-hand-of-god-as-maradona-bids-farewell-to-football-9255781.html|title=Argentina cries for 'that hand of God' as Maradona bids farewell to|date=12 November 2001|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHiguita was imprisoned in 1993 after getting involved in a [[kidnap]]ping. Acting as a go-between for the drug barons [[Pablo Escobar]] and Carlos Molina, he was largely responsible for securing the release of Molina's daughter by delivering the ransom money. He received $64,000 for his services, which breaks Colombian law as it is an offence to profit from a kidnapping. He was incarcerated for seven months before being released without charge. Commenting on the case, he has stated that \"I'm a footballer, I didn't know anything about kidnapping laws.\"<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/en/mens/index/0,2527,103224,00.html?articleid=103224 Ren\u00e9 'el Loco' Higuita leads Ecuador's keepers] \u2013 FIFA.com 22 September 2004 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060515230030/http://www.fifa.com/en/mens/index/0,2527,103224,00.html?articleid=103224 |date=15 May 2006 }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[ESPN]] documentary \"The Two Escobars\", Higuita claimed that he was arrested for visiting Pablo during his time in prison with the desire to thank him for turning himself in thus stabilizing Colombia for a short period. He supported this theory claiming that all he was asked during questioning was solely about Pablo Escobar himself and no kidnapping.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/30for30/film?page=the-two-escobars|title=The Two Escobars - ESPN Films: 30 for 30|website=www.espn.com|language=en|access-date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nBecause of the term in prison Higuita was not fit for the [[1994 FIFA World Cup]]. In another scandal, he tested positive for [[cocaine]] on 23 November 2004 while playing for [[Sociedad Deportiva Aucas|Aucas]], an Ecuadorian football club.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vickery |first=Tim |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_football/4050881.stm |title=Two of the best |publisher=BBC News |date=29 November 2004 |accessdate=30 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/whatever-happened-to-rene-higuita-pablo-escobars-scorpion/1se7sktwrb71a13xputod8n55v|title=Whatever happened to Rene Higuita? Pablo Escobar's scorpion-kicking friend revolutionised goalkeeping {{!}} Goal.com|website=www.goal.com|language=en|access-date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Higuita participated in the reality TV program ''La isla de los famosos: Una aventura pirata'' (\"The Island of the Famous: A Pirate Adventure\"), a show similar to ''[[Survivor (TV series)|Survivor]]''. Also in 2005, he underwent plastic surgery to completely change his appearance.<ref>{{in lang|es}} [http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/441105.html Inconforme Ren\u00e9 Higuita por cambio f\u00edsico a que fue sometido] (''El Universal'')</ref>\n\nHiguita has expressed the wish to become more politically active.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://colombiareports.com/2008/04/01/higuita-wants-to-return-to-colombias-national-team/ |title=Higuita wants to return to Colombia's national team |date=1 April 2008 |publisher=Colombia Reports |accessdate=1 April 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080425061358/http://colombiareports.com/2008/04/01/higuita-wants-to-return-to-colombias-national-team/ <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 25 April 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===International goals===\n''Scores and results lists Colombia's goal tally first.''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/higuita-intl.html|title=Jos\u00e9 Ren\u00e9 Higuita - International Appearances|last=Ballesteros |first=Frank |date=12 February 2006 |website=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible\"\n|-\n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 19 May 1988 || [[Helsinki Olympic Stadium]], [[Helsinki]], Finland || {{fb|FIN}} || <center>2\u20131</center> || <center>3\u20131</center> || [[Exhibition game|Friendly]]\n|-\n| 2. || 3 February 1989 || [[Estadio Centenario (Armenia, Colombia)|Estadio Centenario]], [[Armenia, Colombia|Armenia]], Colombia || {{fb|PER}} || <center>1\u20130</center> || <center>1\u20130</center> || Copa Centenario de Armenia\n|-\n| 3. || 3 July 1989 || [[Est\u00e1dio Fonte Nova]], [[Salvador, Bahia|Salvador]], Brazil || {{fb|VEN}} || <center>1\u20130</center> || <center>4\u20132</center> || [[1989 Copa Am\u00e9rica]]\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n'''Atl\u00e9tico Nacional'''\n*[[Copa Libertadores]]: [[1989 Copa Libertadores|1989]]; Runner-up 1995.\n*[[Copa Interamericana]]: 1990.\n*[[Intercontinental Cup (football)|Intercontinental Cup]]: Runner-up [[1989 Intercontinental Cup|1989]].\n*[[Colombian Professional Football|Colombian League]]: 1991, 1994.\n\n===International===\n'''Colombia'''\n*[[FIFA World Cup]] Round of 16: [[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990]].\n*[[Copa Am\u00e9rica]] Third place: [[1993 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1993]], [[1995 Copa Am\u00e9rica |1995]].\n\n===Individual===\n*South American Team of the Year: 1989, 1990<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/sam-toy.html|title=South American Team of the Year|publisher=RSSSF|date=16 January 2009|accessdate=18 May 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Golden Foot#Award legends|Golden Foot Legends Award]]: 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenfoot.com/legends.php?l=en|title=Legends|publisher=Golden Foot|accessdate=23 September 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925120930/http://www.goldenfoot.com/legends.php?l=en|archivedate=25 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of doping cases in sport]]\n* [[List of goalscoring goalkeepers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Ren\u00e9 Higuita}}\n* {{NFT|13686}}\n* [http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/higuita-intl.html International statistics] at [[rsssf]]\n* [https://www.sportskeeda.com/player/rene-higuita Rene Higuita Career Info and Achievements]\n* [https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/news/newsid=591528.html#higuita+still+going+strong FIFA interview with Ren\u00e9 Higuita]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/timvickery/2010/02/the_legacy_of_rene_higuita.html BBC SPORT Tim Vickery The legacy of Rene Higuita]\n* Ren\u00e9 Higuita clips: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o0NZCSZZj5Q&feature=channel Part 1]; [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6AwnO2cVcbQ&feature=channel Part 2]; [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MKXrSVJZ_nc&feature=channel Part 3]; [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7we1LbA7F30&feature=channel Part 4]\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Colombia squads\n| bg=#FCD116\n| fg=#003893\n| bordercolor=#CE1126\n|list1=\n{{Colombia squad 1987 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Colombia squad 1989 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Colombia squad 1990 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Colombia squad 1991 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Colombia squad 1995 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Colombia squad 1999 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Higuita, Rene}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Medell\u00edn]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers who have scored]]\n[[Category:Colombian footballers]]\n[[Category:Colombia under-20 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Colombia international footballers]]\n[[Category:1990 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:1987 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:1989 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:1991 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:1995 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:1999 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:Millonarios F.C. footballers]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Nacional footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Valladolid players]]\n[[Category:C.D. Veracruz footballers]]\n[[Category:Independiente Medell\u00edn footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Cartagena footballers]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Junior footballers]]\n[[Category:Deportivo Pereira footballers]]\n[[Category:S.D. Aucas footballers]]\n[[Category:Asociaci\u00f3n Civil Deportivo Lara players]]\n[[Category:Leones F.C. footballers]]\n[[Category:Colombian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Categor\u00eda Primera A players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Liga MX players]]\n[[Category:Doping cases in association football]]\n[[Category:Colombian sportspeople in doping cases]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Colombian footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Ren\u00e9 Higuita\n| image = Ren\u00e9 Higuita, 2007.jpg\n| caption= Higuita in 2007\n| fullname = Jos\u00e9 Ren\u00e9 Higuita Zapata\n| height = 1.75 m<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/rene-higuita/|title=Ren\u00e9 Higuita|website=worldfootball.net|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1966|8|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Medell\u00edn]], Colombia\n| currentclub = [[Atl\u00e9tico Nacional]] (goalkeeper coach)\n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[Millonarios FC|Millonarios]]\n| years1 = 1985\n| clubs1 = [[Millonarios FC|Millonarios]]\n| caps1 = 16\n| goals1 = 7\n| years2 = 1986\u20131992\n| clubs2 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Nacional]]\n| caps2 = 112\n| goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 1992\n| clubs3 = [[Real Valladolid]]\n| caps3 = 15\n| goals3 = 2\n| years4 = 1993\u20131997\n| clubs4 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Nacional]]\n| caps4 = 69\n| goals4 = 1\n| years5 = 1997\u20131998\n| clubs5 = [[Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz|Veracruz]]\n| caps5 = 30\n| goals5 = 2\n| years6 = 1999\u20132000\n| clubs6 = [[Independiente Medell\u00edn]]\n| caps6 = 20\n| goals6 = 11\n| years7 = 2000\u20132001\n| clubs7 = [[Real Cartagena]]\n| caps7 = 21\n| goals7 = 0\n| years8 = 2001\u20132002\n| clubs8 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Junior]]\n| caps8 = 4\n| goals8 = 0\n| years9 = 2002\u20132003\n| clubs9 = [[Deportivo Pereira]]\n| caps9 = 13\n| goals9 = 0\n| years10 = 2004\n| clubs10 = [[Sociedad Deportiva Aucas|Aucas]]\n| caps10 = 35\n| goals10 = 3\n| years11 = 2005\n| clubs11 = \n| caps11 = 13\n| goals11 = 1\n| years12 = 2007\n| clubs12 = [[Guaros F\u00fatbol Club|Guaros FC]]\n| caps12 = 10\n| goals12 = 5\n| years13 = 2008\n| clubs13 = [[Leones F. C.|Deportivo Rionegro]]\n| caps13 = 10\n| goals13 = 3\n| years14 = 2008\u20132009\n| clubs14 = [[Deportivo Pereira]]\n| caps14 = 12\n| goals14 = 5\n| totalcaps = 380\n| totalgoals = 41\n| nationalyears1 = 1987\u20131999\n| nationalteam1 = [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]]<ref name=\"International caps and goals\">{{cite web|title=RSSSF|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/higuita-intl.html}}</ref>\n| nationalcaps1 = 68\n| nationalgoals1 = 3\n}}\n{{spanish name 2|Higuita|Zapata}}\n'''Jos\u00e9 Ren\u00e9 Higuita Zapata''' ({{IPA-es|re\u02c8ne i\u02c8\u0263ita}}; born 27 August 1966) is a Colombian former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]]. He was nicknamed ''El Loco'' (\"The Madman\") for his high-risk '[[Goalkeeper (association football)#Sweeper-keeper|sweeper-keeper]]' playing style and his flair for the dramatic.\n\nHiguita's style of play, which was first shown to a global audience during the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]], was pioneering in influencing goalkeepers to take more responsibility for situations further from the goal.<ref name=\"The Legacy of Rene Higuita\">Tim Vickery (10 February 2010). [https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/legacy/timvickery/2010/02/the_legacy_of_rene_higuita.html \"The Legacy of Rene Higuita\"]. BBC. Retrieved 11 June 2014</ref> \n\n[[IFFHS]] ranked Higuita the 8th best keeper in South American in history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/player/rene-higuita|title=Rene Higuita Biography, Career Info, Records & Achievements|website=www.sportskeeda.com|language=en|access-date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe is also ranked as one of the 10 highest-scoring goalkeepers in history, with 41 goals overall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1842588-the-10-best-goalscoring-goalkeepers|title=The 10 Best Goalscoring Goalkeepers|last=Bailey|first=Ryan|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHiguita was born in [[Medell\u00edn]], [[Antioquia Department|Antioquia]] to a single mother, Maria Dioselina. His mother died when he was very young, so his grandma had to take care of him. He was very poor as a child, so he had to work as newspaper mailman and many other jobs in order to survive.\n\n==Club career==\nHiguita started his playing career with [[Millonarios F.C.|Millonarios]] and transferred to [[Atl\u00e9tico Nacional]] in 1986. He played the majority of his club career with the Colombian side where he helped the team win the [[Categor\u00eda Primera A|Colombian League]] on numerous occasions as well as the [[Copa Libertadores]] and [[Copa Interamericana]], both in 1989. After leaving them, he moved to Spain to play with [[Real Valladolid]] for one season, before coming back to Atletico Nacional for four years. He then left to Mexico to play for [[Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz|Veracruz]] before coming back to the Colombian league to play for Atletico's city rivals, [[Independiente Medell\u00edn]].\n\nHe briefly retired in 2005 after failing a drug test while playing for [[Aucas Quito|Aucas]].\n\nHe came out of retirement on 21 July 2007 to sign for Venezuelan club [[Guaros F\u00fatbol Club|Guaros FC]]. In January 2008, aged 41, he signed for the Colombian second division team [[Leones F.C.|Deportivo Rionegro]]. In June 2008 he signed for another Colombia team, [[Deportivo Pereira]], and finally retired on 25 January 2010.<ref>{{cite web|author=Tim Vickery |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/timvickery/2010/02/the_legacy_of_rene_higuita.html |title=The legacy of Rene Higuita |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=30 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Higuita pateando.jpg|thumb|150px|Higuita in the training sessions with Colombia during the 1990 World Cup]]\nHiguita's first major tournament was the [[1989 Copa Am\u00e9rica]], where the team was knocked out in the first round. In the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]], he played an important part to lead the country into the round of 16 for the first time ever. However, Higuita's unorthodox playing style caused a mistake by him that knocked Colombia out of the World Cup, when he tried to feint [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]] striker [[Roger Milla]] but failed, and Milla dispossessed him and scored, which put Cameroon through to the quarter-finals. Higuita described it as \"a mistake as big as a house\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-fa-cup---schmeichel-slices-into-fixture-jam-1145084.html|title=Schmeichel slices into fixture|last=Shaw|first=Phil|date=16 February 1998|work=The Independent}}</ref> As a result of such behaviour, Higuita was nicknamed ''El Loco'' (\"The Madman\").<ref name=\"scorpion kick keeper\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-12792304|title=Colombia 'scorpion kick' keeper Higuita runs for mayor|date=19 March 2011|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nHe played in the [[1991 Copa Am\u00e9rica]] where the team finished fourth. His last call up for the national team was for the [[1999 Copa Am\u00e9rica]].\n\nHiguita often took set-pieces for the [[Colombia national football team|Colombian national team]], in all, he scored three goals in his 68 international appearances.\n\n==Style of play==\nOn the pitch, Higuita was known for his dramatic flair, composure under pressure, and eccentric playing style, often taking unnecessary risks and actively coming out of his area to anticipate opponents, play the ball out to defenders, undertake individual dribbling runs, and attempt to score goals, which led him to be described as a '[[sweeper-keeper]]'; he was therefore a pioneer in influencing other goalkeepers to take more responsibility for situations further away from the goal.<ref name=\"The Legacy of Rene Higuita\"/> Although he was a goalkeeper, Higuita also became known for scoring directly from [[Direct free kick|free-kicks]], as well as [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalties]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/33006305|title=Rogerio Ceni: Sao Paulo keeper into club record books|publisher=BBC|date=4 June 2015|accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nHis style of play led to the creation of the [[Back-pass rule]], which is also known as the ''Higuita Law.''\n\n[[IFFHS]] ranked Higuita the 8th best keeper in South American history. \n\nHiguita's style of play, which was first shown to a global audience during the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]], was pioneering in influencing goalkeepers to take more responsibility for situations further from the goal.\n\n====Scorpion Kick====\nFurthermore, Higuita reportedly invented the [[scorpion kick]], a movement which involves the player jumping forward, positioning their legs over their head, and in doing so, kicks the ball away with their heels; one of Higuita's most notable uses of the scorpion was when he performed it while clearing a cross from [[Jamie Redknapp]] during a friendly against [[England national football team|England]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] on 6 September 1995, earning him considerable media attention.<ref name=\"scorpion kick keeper\" /> It ranked 94th in [[Channel 4]]'s ''[[100 Greatest Sporting Moments]]'' in 2002.<ref name=\"UK poll\">[http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/G/greatest_sporting/results.html 100 Greatest sporting moments \u2013 results] ''[[Channel 4]]''. Retrieved 28 August 2014</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nHiguita has expressed the wish to coach the Colombian national team and in December 2008 he got the job of goalkeeper coach for his former club [[Real Valladolid]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://elvalladolid.com/articles/8531-rene-higuita-nuevo-preparador-de-porteros |title=Ren\u00e9 Higuita, nuevo preparador de porteros en |publisher=Elvalladolid.com |accessdate=30 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090917201325/http://elvalladolid.com/articles/8531-rene-higuita-nuevo-preparador-de-porteros |archivedate=17 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nHe joined [[Al Nassr FC]] in Saudi Arabia in 2011, and was the club goalkeeper coach for about 5 years, until 2016. \n\nHe rejoined Atletico Nacional on 28 June 2017 after receiving a coaching job as the goalkeeping coach. Upon rejoining, he said \"the dream of my life was to return to Atletico Nacional\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/football/other-football/scorpion-kick-goalkeeper-higuita-joins-atletico-nacional/article19163654.ece|title=Scorpion kick goalkeeper Higuita joins Atletico Nacional|last=Lines|first=Oliver|website=Sportstar|language=en|access-date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHiguita is married to Magnolia, with whom he has three children, Andr\u00e9s, Pamela and Wilfred. He also has a daughter, Cindy Carolina, from a previous marriage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?q=rene+higuita+children&rlz=1C1ZKTG_enUS831US832&oq=rene+higuita+children&aqs=chrome..69i57.3921j0j4&sourceid=chrome&ie=UTF-8|title=rene higuita children - Google Search|website=www.google.com|access-date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe is friends with [[Diego Maradona]] and played in the Argentine's farewell match in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/argentina-cries-for-that-hand-of-god-as-maradona-bids-farewell-to-football-9255781.html|title=Argentina cries for 'that hand of God' as Maradona bids farewell to|date=12 November 2001|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHiguita was imprisoned in 1993 after getting involved in a [[kidnap]]ping. Acting as a go-between for the drug barons [[Pablo Escobar]] and Carlos Molina, he was largely responsible for securing the release of Molina's daughter by delivering the ransom money. He received $64,000 for his services, which breaks Colombian law as it is an offence to profit from a kidnapping. He was incarcerated for seven months before being released without charge. Commenting on the case, he has stated that \"I'm a footballer, I didn't know anything about kidnapping laws.\"<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/en/mens/index/0,2527,103224,00.html?articleid=103224 Ren\u00e9 'el Loco' Higuita leads Ecuador's keepers] \u2013 FIFA.com 22 September 2004 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060515230030/http://www.fifa.com/en/mens/index/0,2527,103224,00.html?articleid=103224 |date=15 May 2006 }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[ESPN]] documentary \"The Two Escobars\", Higuita claimed that he was arrested for visiting Pablo during his time in prison with the desire to thank him for turning himself in thus stabilizing Colombia for a short period. He supported this theory claiming that all he was asked during questioning was solely about Pablo Escobar himself and no kidnapping.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/30for30/film?page=the-two-escobars|title=The Two Escobars - ESPN Films: 30 for 30|website=www.espn.com|language=en|access-date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nBecause of the term in prison Higuita was not fit for the [[1994 FIFA World Cup]]. In another scandal, he tested positive for [[cocaine]] on 23 November 2004 while playing for [[Sociedad Deportiva Aucas|Aucas]], an Ecuadorian football club.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vickery |first=Tim |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_football/4050881.stm |title=Two of the best |publisher=BBC News |date=29 November 2004 |accessdate=30 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/whatever-happened-to-rene-higuita-pablo-escobars-scorpion/1se7sktwrb71a13xputod8n55v|title=Whatever happened to Rene Higuita? Pablo Escobar's scorpion-kicking friend revolutionised goalkeeping {{!}} Goal.com|website=www.goal.com|language=en|access-date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Higuita participated in the reality TV program ''La isla de los famosos: Una aventura pirata'' (\"The Island of the Famous: A Pirate Adventure\"), a show similar to ''[[Survivor (TV series)|Survivor]]''. Also in 2005, he underwent plastic surgery to completely change his appearance.<ref>{{in lang|es}} [http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/441105.html Inconforme Ren\u00e9 Higuita por cambio f\u00edsico a que fue sometido] (''El Universal'')</ref>\n\nHiguita has expressed the wish to become more politically active.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://colombiareports.com/2008/04/01/higuita-wants-to-return-to-colombias-national-team/ |title=Higuita wants to return to Colombia's national team |date=1 April 2008 |publisher=Colombia Reports |accessdate=1 April 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080425061358/http://colombiareports.com/2008/04/01/higuita-wants-to-return-to-colombias-national-team/ <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 25 April 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===International goals===\n''Scores and results lists Colombia's goal tally first.''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/higuita-intl.html|title=Jos\u00e9 Ren\u00e9 Higuita - International Appearances|last=Ballesteros |first=Frank |date=12 February 2006 |website=The Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible\"\n|-\n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 19 May 1988 || [[Helsinki Olympic Stadium]], [[Helsinki]], Finland || {{fb|FIN}} || <center>'''2'''\u20131</center> || <center>3\u20131</center> || [[Exhibition game|Friendly]]\n|-\n| 2. || 3 February 1989 || [[Estadio Centenario (Armenia, Colombia)|Estadio Centenario]], [[Armenia, Colombia|Armenia]], Colombia || {{fb|PER}} || <center>'''1'''\u20130</center> || <center>1\u20130</center> || Copa Centenario de Armenia\n|-\n| 3. || 3 July 1989 || [[Est\u00e1dio Fonte Nova]], [[Salvador, Bahia|Salvador]], Brazil || {{fb|VEN}} || <center>'''1'''\u20130</center> || <center>4\u20132</center> || [[1989 Copa Am\u00e9rica]]\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n'''Atl\u00e9tico Nacional'''\n*[[Copa Libertadores]]: [[1989 Copa Libertadores|1989]]; Runner-up 1995.\n*[[Copa Interamericana]]: 1990.\n*[[Intercontinental Cup (football)|Intercontinental Cup]]: Runner-up [[1989 Intercontinental Cup|1989]].\n*[[Colombian Professional Football|Colombian League]]: 1991, 1994.\n\n===International===\n'''Colombia'''\n*[[FIFA World Cup]] Round of 16: [[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990]].\n*[[Copa Am\u00e9rica]] Third place: [[1993 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1993]], [[1995 Copa Am\u00e9rica |1995]].\n\n===Individual===\n*South American Team of the Year: 1989, 1990<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/sam-toy.html|title=South American Team of the Year|publisher=RSSSF|date=16 January 2009|accessdate=18 May 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Golden Foot#Award legends|Golden Foot Legends Award]]: 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenfoot.com/legends.php?l=en|title=Legends|publisher=Golden Foot|accessdate=23 September 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925120930/http://www.goldenfoot.com/legends.php?l=en|archivedate=25 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of doping cases in sport]]\n* [[List of goalscoring goalkeepers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Ren\u00e9 Higuita}}\n* {{NFT|13686}}\n* [http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/higuita-intl.html International statistics] at [[rsssf]]\n* [https://www.sportskeeda.com/player/rene-higuita Rene Higuita Career Info and Achievements]\n* [https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/news/newsid=591528.html#higuita+still+going+strong FIFA interview with Ren\u00e9 Higuita]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/timvickery/2010/02/the_legacy_of_rene_higuita.html BBC SPORT Tim Vickery The legacy of Rene Higuita]\n* Ren\u00e9 Higuita clips: [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o0NZCSZZj5Q&feature=channel Part 1]; [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6AwnO2cVcbQ&feature=channel Part 2]; [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MKXrSVJZ_nc&feature=channel Part 3]; [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7we1LbA7F30&feature=channel Part 4]\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Colombia squads\n| bg=#FCD116\n| fg=#003893\n| bordercolor=#CE1126\n|list1=\n{{Colombia squad 1987 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Colombia squad 1989 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Colombia squad 1990 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Colombia squad 1991 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Colombia squad 1995 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Colombia squad 1999 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Higuita, Rene}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Medell\u00edn]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers who have scored]]\n[[Category:Colombian footballers]]\n[[Category:Colombia under-20 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Colombia international footballers]]\n[[Category:1990 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:1987 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:1989 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:1991 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:1995 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:1999 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:Millonarios F.C. footballers]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Nacional footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Valladolid players]]\n[[Category:C.D. Veracruz footballers]]\n[[Category:Independiente Medell\u00edn footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Cartagena footballers]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Junior footballers]]\n[[Category:Deportivo Pereira footballers]]\n[[Category:S.D. Aucas footballers]]\n[[Category:Asociaci\u00f3n Civil Deportivo Lara players]]\n[[Category:Leones F.C. footballers]]\n[[Category:Colombian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Categor\u00eda Primera A players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Liga MX players]]\n[[Category:Doping cases in association football]]\n[[Category:Colombian sportspeople in doping cases]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer statistics:Remove bold formatting.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ren%C3%A9_Higuita"}
{"title_page": "Pieter Pourbus", "text_new": "\n\n{{copyedit|date=March 2020}}\n'''Pieter Jansz. Pourbus''' (c. 1523, in [[Gouda, South Holland|Gouda]] \u2013 30 January 1584, in [[Bruges]]) was a [[Dutch and Flemish Renaissance painting|Flemish Renaissance painter]], draftsman, engineer and cartographer who was active in Bruges during the 16th century.  He is known primarily for his religious and portrait painting.<ref name=RKD>.[https://rkd.nl/en/explore/artists/64551 Pieter Pourbus] at the [[Netherlands Institute for Art History]] {{in lang|nl}}</ref>\n[[File:The Annunciation, by Pieter Pourbus.jpg|thumb|450px|''The Annunciation'',1552, Museum Gouda, Netherlands, oil on panel, 117 x 112 cm, signed c.: 1552 / PETRVS POVRBUS ME FECIT]]\n\n== Life ==\n=== Birth and origin ===\nPieter Pourbus was born in Gouda in 1523 or 1524.  He moved to Bruges at the age of 20.<br>\n\nVery little is known on his childhood and youth, at the time when he lived in Gouda. <br>\nAll sources only make a brief mention of his origins.<br>\n\n===== Gouda =====\nHis first biography was written by contemporary artist biographer [[Karel_van_Mander|Karel van Mander]] in his renowned \"Painting Book\" (\"Schilder-boeck\") of 1604<ref>Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''\"Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda\"'', 2018. Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda. 86 pages. Article written by Paul H.A.M. Abels, \u00a7.1, page 31</ref>.<br>\n\"Even so, I would not like to conceal any of the most special. That is why I wish to present this view of\nPieter Pourbus\". <br>\n\"Born in the Dutch town of Gouda, he based himself in Bruges from an early age\".<ref>Van Mander 1604, fol. 257r; original text in Dutch:''\u2018\u2026Evenwel soud\u2019 ick niet geern eenige der besonderste verzwijgen. Daerom ick hier wil voor ooghen stellen Pieter Pourbus.\u2019''</ref> <br>\nWith these words, [[Karel_van_Mander|Karel van Mander]], the author of the 1604 work \"Het Schilder-Boeck, over t\u2019 leven der Vermaerde Doorluchtighe Schilders\" (\"The Book of Painters, about the life of Renowned Honourable Painters\") describes his colleague from Bruges.<br>\nKarel remembers him as \"the painter of Bruges\".<br>\nThe two met in 1580, when [[Karel_van_Mander|Van Mander]] fled the ravages of the Eighty Years\u2019 War and stayed in Bruges for a time. <br>\nPourbus must have overwhelmed him with information about all of the beautiful sights of Bruges at that time, as he was the source for most of the information [[Karel_van_Mander|Van Mander]] provides regarding the Bruges school of painting.<ref>Article written by Paul Huvenne, \u00a7.1 page 9, in Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''\"Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda\"'', 2018. Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda. 86 pages</ref><br>\n\nWe do not have any portrait or self portrait of Pieter Pourbus, but he probably included his own portrait on the left altar wing of the \"Tryptych of the Holy Sacrament fraternity\" in the St Saviour's Cathedral, Bruges.<br>\n\nAt the time, Pourbus was not considered a native in Bruges itself.\nWhen he registers as a master painter with the guild of Sculptors and Saddlers in 1543 as \"Pieter Jansyns Poerbus\", he is explicitly marked \"as a stranger\" (\u2018vrymde\u2019) in the records. He must have been 19 or 20 years old at the time, based on the mentions of his age in a range of documents. From there, we can conclude that he must have been born in 1523 or 1524. <br>\n\nAt the occasion of the exhibition on Pieter Pourbus at the Gouda Museum in 2018, Paul Abels wrote in the catalogue of this exhibition on the role Gouda played in his life by putting what little is known about his ties to the city in the context of late-medieval religious and social life In Gouda.<ref>Article written by Paul H.A.M. Abels, \u00a7.1, page 31, in Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''\"Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda\"'', 2018. Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda. 86 pages</ref>\n\nHe mentioned that the name Pourbus features several times in Gouda at the start of the sixteenth century. <br>\nBut he adds that only one person in the Gouda city archives who would actually qualify as Pourbus\u2019 father, namely \"Jan Pieterssoen Puerboss\", who features in the city accounts in 1529. The accounts mention a payment made to him for \"painting the board that stands in front of the window\". The mention is brief, but it allows to corroborate [[Karel_van_Mander|Van Mander\u2019s]] claim about Pourbus\u2019 Gouda roots by another contemporary source. <br>\nThis source also shows that he was also a painter, although it is not possible to know what his real artistic skills were. The mention most likely refers to painting a (town\u2019s) coat of arms on a shutter.<ref>Paul H.A.M. Abels, \u00a7. page 31, in Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda'', 2018. Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda. 86 pages</ref>\n\n===== From Gouda to Bruges =====\nPourbus\u2019 move to Bruges can be explained because Bruges is known to be a city that produces excellent painting, although that reputation is waning slightly when Pourbus arrives.<br>\nBruges is familiar territory for the Gouda residents. Pourbus will have heard many stories about the city of Bruges when growing up. The two cities are closely connected by the beer trade, which was the leading line of business in Gouda at the time.<br>\n\nBefore he went to Bruges, he may have studied his craft with Utrecht-based painters such as [[Jan_van_Scorel|Jan van Scorel]] or the Leiden masters. Recent technical research suggests Leiden, more so than Utrecht.<br>\n[[Lucas_van_Leyden|Lucas van Leyden]] and [[Cornelis_Engebrechtsz.|Cornelis Engelbrechtsz]] pass away when Pourbus is still a child, but he may have come into contact with Engelbrechtsz\u2019s three sons, [[Cornelis Cornelisz Kunst|Cornelis]], [[Lucas Cornelisz de Kock|Lucas]], and [[Pieter Cornelisz. Kunst]], who followed in their father\u2019s footsteps and became painters in their own right.<br>\n\n=== Pourbus in Bruges ===\nShortly after he registers with the \u2019Sculptors and Saddlers\u2019 Guild in Bruges in 1543 ( the Bruges \"[[Guild_of_Saint_Luke|Guild of Saint Luke]]\"), Pieter Pourbus marries. He weds Anna, the youngest daughter of painter [[Lancelot_Blondeel|Lancelot Blondeel]]. His marriage to the daughter of an established artist lacking any male heirs is very important for his reputation and further career as a master painter.<ref>from the article written by Paul H.A.M. Abels, \u00a7. page 34, in: Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''\"Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda\"'', 2018. Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda. 86 pages</ref> <br>\nIn 1545 or 1546, she bears him a son, Frans ([[Frans_Pourbus_the_Elder|\u2018the elder\u2019]]), who is predestined to take up his father\u2019s brush after him. Pourbus integrates into the city of Bruges with ease. <br>\nHe becomes a member of the crossbowmen\u2019s guild of St George and often visits the rhetorician meetings organised by the Chamber of the Holy Spirit. [[Lancelot_Blondeel|Blondeel]], who is a well-respected person there, may have introduced him.<br>\nIt is unclear where Pourbus\u2019 initial training as a painter took place. Recent research into his underdrawings\npoints in the direction of Leiden.6 Very few concrete details of his first few years in Bruges are known. It would appear that he initially operated from under the wing of his successful father-in-law.<ref>Paul Huvenne, in Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda: Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''\"Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda\"'', 2018.  86 pages. \u00a7.1 page 11</ref>\n===== Working in Blondeel's studio =====\n[[Lancelot_Blondeel|Blondeel]], perhaps the most authoritative artist of his generation in Bruges, introduced an early form of Italian renaissance painting.<br>\n[[File:Pieter Pourbus - Last Supper - WGA18255.jpg|thumb|right|350px|Pieter Pourbus - ''The last Supper'', 1548 - 46,5x63cm - [[Groeningemuseum]], Bruges]]\nPourbus\u2019 earliest work is in line with this school of painting. \nIn fact, it remains unclear in some cases whether the works are the result of collaboration or whether they were painted by him individually, for instance in the case of ''\"The Seven Joys of the Virgin\"'', which hangs in the Tournai Cathedral, for which these two artists join forces.<br>\n\nPourbus\u2019 smaller work ''\"Last Supper\"''<ref>Pourbus made later five other depictions of the Last Supper (all of imposing size) in addition to the present painting, including the 1559 Triptych of the Brotherhood of the Sacrament (Saint James Church, Bruges) and that of 1562 in the Onze Lieve Vrouwekerk, Bruges. <br>\nThe former still retains its original double-sided wings, the left one showing Melchisedech\u2019s Offering and the right one, Elijah Fed by the Angel, </ref> indicates that his father-in-law also introduced him to the ''\u2018Rederijker\u2019'' or rhetorician circles of amateur poets and reciting artists.<br>\n\nThis little painting depicts the Last Supper as described in the Refrains of rhetorician [https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eduard_de_Dene Edward van Dene].<br>\n\nNote on this small painting a rare iconography for this subject, with the presence of a devil entering the room on the right of the painting.\n\n[[File:Pierre pourbus-triptico de los santos juanes-prado.jpg|thumb|center|750px|Pieter Pourbus - Triptych of '' \"Baptism of Christ\" '', 1549, 241x377cm - [[Prado Museum]], Madrid]]<br>\n\nIt is unclear exactly when Pourbus began working for himself. <br>\nFor example, he began painting for the Spanish art market at an early stage. <br>\nHis monumental triptych ''\"The Baptism of Christ\"'', which dates back to 1549 and now hangs in the Museo del Prado in Madrid, indicates how grand these commissions can be.<br>\n\nOne of his works was recently unearthed, the Spanish epitaph of Martin Cruzat, which dates back to 1548. <br>\nThis is a classic Piet\u00e0 featuring the deceased\u2019s portrait, evidently intended for the grave in his parish church in Pamplona. <br>\nThe piece was on display for the public for the first time at the exhibition of the Museum Gouda in 2018.<br>\n\nAnother work that dates back to Pourbus\u2019 early years in Bruges is his only remaining non-religious history work, ''\"An Allegory of True Love\"'', currently part of the Wallace Collection in London. <br>\n[[File:Pieter Pourbus - Allegory of true love.jpg|thumb|550px|center| Pieter Pourbus - ''Allegory of true love'', c. 1547 - 132,8x205,7cm - Wallace collection, London]]This painting shows Pourbus\u2019s painting style as truly innovative.<ref>Paul Huvenne, in Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda: Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda'', 2018. 86 pages. \u00a7.2 page 11</ref><br>\n\n===== Out of Blondeel's shadow =====\n[[File:Pieter Pourbus Portret1.jpg|thumb|200px|Pieter Pourbus ''Portrait of Jan van Eyewerve'', 1551 - [[Groeningemuseum]], Bruges]] [[File:Pieter Pourbus Portret2.jpg|thumb|200px|Pieter Pourbus ''Portrait of Jacquemyne Buuck'', 1551, [[Groeningemuseum]], Bruges]]As from 1549, Pourbus leaves his father-in-law\u2019s shadow. From this moment on, his name starts appearing in all sorts of historical documents with great frequency. <br>\nHe is named yearly, and sometimes even daily, in many official sources. <br>\nSome notable commissions will also have played a role in increasing his fame, such as the decorations for the Joyous entry of Charles V and prince Philip II in 1549 (\u2018Blijde intocht van Karel V en prins Filips in 1549\u2019), a design for a new banquet hall, and a ''\"Last Judgment\"'' (''\u2018Laatste Oordeel\u2019''); all of these are commissions for the so-called ''\u2018Brugse Vrije\u2019'' (also known as the Liberty of Bruges), the legally autonomous territory of Bruges.<br>\n\nAnother prominent commission was his works for the mausoleum of Margaret of Austria at the Annunciation Convent in Bruges, which the magnificent Annunciation currently displayed at Museum Gouda was part of.\nPourbus gradually became the preferred master painter of the bourgeoisie, such as wine merchant Jan van Eyewerve and his wife Jacquemyne Buuck. They had their portraits painted to celebrate their wedding. <br>\n\nThe fact that Pourbus expressly dates and signs his works throughout this period is indicative of the rise in his confidence.<br>\n\n\nPourbus also made many topographic maps. <br>\nHe began using a new methodology based on triangulation that resulted in very modern-looking maps.13 It was a new format for visual reports intended to support surveyors\u2019 legal reports. <br>\nIt is unknown how Pourbus obtained this knowledge, but his 1549 map of the canal between Damme and Sluis indicates that he was most likely already using the new technique at that time, constituting a grand innovative move in 1540s Bruges.<br>\nAll of this hard work paid off: in 1552, Pourbus bought Huis Rome (\u2018the Rome House\u2019) on the Heer Jan Admiraelstraat. [[Karel_van_Mander|Van Mander]] later writes that here, Pourbus set up the best painting studio he ever saw.<ref>Paul Huvenne, in Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda: Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda'', 2018. 86 pages. \u00a7.2 page 13</ref>\n\n===== Active Guild member =====\nAs from 1551, Pourbus became a prominent and active member of his guild\u2019s council; he served two terms as dean of the guild and five terms as sworn elder. He was very committed to his guild duties; for example, as an elder, he participated in quality checks on fellow guild members. He visited Simon Puseel in response to the latter\u2019s poor performance in gilding the dome of the Jerusalem Chapel in Bruges. As a dean, he acted to prevent paintings from Dordrecht being sold inside the city walls. He also defended the guild\u2019s interests several times in the leasing of land it owned in the province of Zeeland. Clearly, Pourbus was a very active and committed member of the Bruges Guild of Sculptors and Saddlers.<ref>Paul Huvenne, in Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda: Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda'', 2018. 86 pages. \u00a7.2 page 16</ref>\n\n=== Pourbus\u2019 best years ===\nThe decade following his breakthrough in 1550 boasts the best work of his career.<br>\n\n===== Pourbus truly surpasses himself as a portraitist =====\nPourbus\u2019 fine portrait of Joris (?) van den Heede, whose family motto \"sint sine dentes sales\" (\"be witty without spite\") was taken word for word from Erasmus\u2019 introduction to \"In Praise of Folly\", is reminiscent of that of Jan van Eyewerve.\n\nAnd with his portraits of \"Pieter Dominicle and his wife Livina van der Beke\", Pourbus truly surpasses himself as a portraitist.<br>\n[[File:Pieter Pourbus . Portrait of a young lady.1554.signed and dated.jpg|thumb|275px|Pieter Pourbus.''Portrait of a noble young lady''.signed and dated 1554.<br>\nPrivate collection]]\nThe captivating elegance with which he portrays women is even more evident in this smaller \"Portrait of a noble young lady\", from a private collection.<br>\nUnfortunately, no inscription or family crest is to be seen on the painting, neither could it be found after IR or X rays examination. It is therefore impossible to identify the lady depicted, but her rich dress, distinguished appearance, and self-aware gaze shows that this is a lady of considerable standing.<br>\nHer dress, with its delicate lace collar, allowed [http://vlaamseprimitieven.vlaamsekunstcollectie.be/en/research/researchers/paul-huvenne Paul Huvenne]<ref>https://www.codart.nl/museums/kmska-director-paul-huvenne-to-retire-on-1-august/</ref>, who discovered this painting, to date the portrait as having been painted before 1560.<br>\nAnd indeed the IR examination revealed Pourbus' monogram, as well as the year when he painted this captivating portrait: 1554.<br>\nAs [http://vlaamseprimitieven.vlaamsekunstcollectie.be/en/research/researchers/paul-huvenne Paul Huvenne]<ref>https://www.codart.nl/museums/kmska-director-paul-huvenne-to-retire-on-1-august/</ref> writes it, it is one of the finest example of Pourbus\u2019 portrait style, and probably the masterwork among its intimate portraits:<br>\n\"He manages to lift the striking likeness that is expected of any portrait to an icon that radiates societal and spiritual values. In doing so, he endows the person depicted with a detached, but animated beauty that leaves no one unmoved\"<ref>Paul Huvenne, in Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda: Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda'', 2018. 86 pages. \u00a7.3 page 16 and 17</ref>.<br>\nIn an article published at the occasion of the exhibition at the Gouda Museum, another author describes this portrait as [https://marccouwenbergh.nl/de-mona-lisa-van-pieter-pourbus-meester-schilder-uit-gouda/ '''the Mona Lisa of Pourbus\"'']. <br>\nMoreover, in a detailed following article<ref>https://marccouwenbergh.nl/anna-van-bueren-versus-de-mona-lisa-van-pieter-pourbus-meester-schilder-uit-gouda/</ref>, he draws attention on many similarities between this portrait and the portrait of [[Anna van Egmont]], first wife of [[William the Silent|William of Orange]], belonging to the Royal collection, The Hague. The comparison can also be found [[Anna_van_Egmont#A_newly_discovered_portrait_of_Anna_van_Egmont?|here]].<br>\n\nHis art as a portraitist is also revealed during this decade by group portraits that are second to none. <br>\nThe wing-panels with portraits of the Members of the Noble Confraternity of the Holy Blood and the Sacra Confrerie of St Salvators is a wonderful example. <br>\nThe position of the sitters suggest that Pourbus must have envisioned the work of Utrecht-based painter [[Jan_van_Scorel|Jan van Scorel]].<br>\n\n===== History painter  =====\nPourbus is now also able to prove himself as a history painter.<br>\n\nHe follows up on his impressive Last Judgment, now part of the Groeningemuseum\u2019s collection, and the beautiful Annunciation in Museum Gouda with the smaller Crucifixion in 1557.<br>\n[[File:Pourbus-Vanbelle-Triptiek.jpg|thumb|left|500px|Pourbus - ''\"Van Belle Triptych\"'',1556 - St James' church, Bruges]]\nBut more than any other work, the Van Belle triptych illustrates how Pourbus\u2019 style has matured.<br>\nIn many ways, this triptych is a key piece in his oeuvre, not only because it is one of his best paintings, but also because it is so well documented in archival materials.\nFor example, one of the items that survived is the original design drawing that Pourbus presented to Joos Van Belle for his approval.<br>\nThe sheet bears handwritten comments, in which the artist agrees to portray the Madonna not with clenched hands but in a more resigned posture: ''\u2018with the arms pressed crosswise over one another\u2019''. The theme of Our Lady of the Seven Sorrows on the middle panel was a very popular one in Pourbus\u2019 day, and it will have been quite a challenge for the artist to come up with a new, convincing composition to depict the theme.\nPourbus\u2019 depiction of the Virgin Mary owes much to the statue of the Madonna with Child by Michelangelo at the Church of Our Lady in Bruges.<br>\n\nThe success that is now due to Pourbus is confirmed by his 1558 Piet\u00e0 at the \u00c9glise Saint-Maurice in Annecy and\nhis Adoration of the Golden Calf, painted around 1559, currently in show at the National Gallery in Dublin.<br>\n\nPourbus becomes the leading representative of the Italian High Renaissance as propagated in Antwerp by [[Frans_Floris|Frans Floris]]. This is a stylistic idiom that is completely contrary to the deep-seated gothic tradition. \nOne example of this high renaissance style is the grotesques in which he depicts the portraits of Mr and Mrs Ghuyse-Van Male.<br>\nAt this point, Pourbus\u2019 work features more translucent, confident brushwork and a clear composition style that manages to reconcile tradition and innovation. These aspects are readily apparent in the Van Belle triptych, in which he paraphrases the composition of Jan van Eyck\u2019s [[Virgin_and_Child_with_Canon_van_der_Paele|\"The Virgin and Child with Canon Van der Paele\"]] from 1436, which is now part of the collection at the Groeningemuseum in Bruges.<br>\nWith his innovation of the style, Pourbus makes his mark on the artistic production in Bruges and the surrounding area. As such, the Italian [[Lodovico_Guicciardini|Ludovico Guicciardini]] names him as one of the most important painters of his time in his ''\"Descrittione di tutti i Paesi Bassi\"'' or ''\"Description of all the Low Countries\"'' in 1567.<ref>Paul Huvenne, in Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda: Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''\"Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda\"'', 2018.  86 pages. page 16 to 20</ref>\n\n===== The leading painter in Bruges =====\n[[File:Portrait of a woman with unknown coat of arms, 1565 -National Galleries of Scotland, ,Edinburg.jpg|thumb |Pieter Pourbus - ''Portrait of a woman with unknown coat of arms'', 1565 - [https://www.nationalgalleries.org National Galleries of Scotland], Edinburg]]\nLancelot Blondeel passes away in 1561.<br>\n\nPourbus is now the leading painter in Bruges.<br>\n\nIn the years that follow, he teaches many an apprentice, including his son Frans, and [[Antoon_Claeissens|Antonius Claeissens]], who starts working for him at one point.<br>\n\nBusiness is going well, but artistically speaking, Pourbus appears to stagnate somewhat during this period.\nSeveral altar pieces that date from this period are a far cry from his best work. <br>\n\nHowever, he does show his skills as an exquisite portraitist from time to time, such as in this Portrait of a twenty-six years old woman from Edinburg. <br>\n\nIn spite of the coat of arms, this young lady has not yet been identified. It has been suggested that she might be part of the De Grave family, who are originally from Flanders but settled in Andalusia.\nIf so, this would once again be a nod to the Spanish presence in Bruges at the time.<br>\n\nThe portrait displays such immense refinement and grace that it was taken to be a portrait of Mary Stuart, Queen of Scots for much of the nineteenth century. <br>\n\nWith his smooth, enamel-like stylisation, Pourbus has imbued the woman\u2019s face with an introverted and enigmatic quality. <br>\nIt is reminiscent of [[Lodovico_Guicciardini|Guicciardini\u2019s]] assertions that in Bruges, ''\u2018the women are as beautiful, lovely, modest and temperate as in any city in these lands\u2019''.<br>\n\n[[File:Pieter Pourbus - Portrait of Jan Lopez Gallo and His Three Sons - WGA18256.jpg|thumb|left|Pieter Pourbus - ''Portrait of Jan Lopez Gallo and His Three Sons'', 1568 - [https://www.museabrugge.be/en/visit-our-museums/our-museums-and-monuments/groeningemuseum Groeningen Museum], Bruges]]\n[[File:Francois Van der Straeten.jpg|thumb|450pix|Pieter Pourbus - ''Portrait de Francois Van der Straeten'', 1567 - [https://www.museummayervandenbergh.be/en Mayer Van Den Bergh Museum], Anvers]]\n\nIn 1567, Pourbus produces yet another portrait, of Knight Fran\u00e7ois van der Straten. <br>\n\nHe draws inspiration from an allegorical print by Cornelis Theunisz from 1537 in which a child, an hourglass, and a skull remind one of the transience of life in much the same way.<br>\n\nVan der Straten was a leading authority in the Liberty of Bruges and an academically trained lawyer. <br>\n\nThe text that he points out on the note beneath his hand reads as follows: \"COGNITIO DEI ET NATVRAE RATIONANIS\" (''\"Knowledge of God and the Reasonable Nature\"'').<br>\nThis is a reference to his humanist view of life.<br>\nHis motto, \"ABSIT GLORIA\" (\"reject glory\"), once again brings to mind the notion of vanitas.<br>\n\nIn the same year, he also paints the portrait of Pieter de Corte, the freshly appointed bishop of the recently created bishopric of Bruges. <br>\nDe Corte was appointed by King Philip II of Spain. Considering the prestige involved in this commission, it was naturally granted to Pourbus.<br>\n\nHis Portrait of Juan Lopez Gallo and his sons, dating back to 1568, once again prove that the ties with his Spanish clientele had not weakened in the slightest.<br>\nHis work can even be found on the Canary Islands. There, Pourbus dealt with his clients\u2019 differing customs in a very special way, by adjusting the size of his retables to suit the size of altar that was customary in Spain at the time.<br>\nSometimes, he leaves the actual execution of paintings for his more distant clients to atelier staff, as shown in his \"Mount at Calvary\", presently in the Cathedral of San Pedro in Soria.<br>\n\n===== The year of the great map =====\nHis most important commission of the 1560s is the monumental Map of the Liberty of Bruges [fi g. 14]. <br>\nThe accounts allow us to trace Pourbus\u2019 steps almost on a daily basis during the many days he spends on this work. The documents tell us all about how he adapted existing materials or created new ones, who worked on the map with him, who came along with him (such as lawyers, surveyors, and magistrates), and how he repeatedly presented his progress to the client. He completed this magnum opus in 1571.<br>\n\n=== From 1570 to Pourbus death ===\n===== The 1570's =====\nAfter the enormous effort of the Great Map, it seems Pourbus had more time for regular commissions once\nagain. <br>\nHis students have since left his studio. His son [[Frans_Pourbus_the_Elder|Frans]] left for Antwerp in 1569 to make his fortune as a painter there, and [[Antonius Claeissens]] became the official city painter of Bruges in 1570. <br>\nPourbus continues to paint portraits without a moment\u2019s rest.[[File:Pieter Pourbus - Portrait of Olivier van Nieulant - WGA18257.jpg|thumb|left|200px| Pieter Pourbus - ''Portrait of Olivier van Nieulant'', 1573 - 49,5 \u00d7 37,5 cm, <br>[https://www.kmska.be/en Museum of Fine Arts], Antwerp]]\nHis style does change slightly, as evidenced by his portrait of Olivier Nieulant dated 1573, which is now in the Royal Museum of Fine Arts Antwerp.\n\nHis brushwork becomes less transparent and more enamel-like. This shift is also apparent in his history paintings, such as the Altarpiece of St Hubert in the collection of Museum Gouda.\nThe shift lends a cooler appearance, a more classicist quality to his work, but also makes it slightly more rigid.<br>\n\nIt is remarkable how well Pourbus is able to focus his compositions or inventions on the Italian renaissance\nidiom, considering the fact that he never went to Italy.\nA good example of this, once again, is the Altarpiece of St Hubert, painted before 1572, which is praised by [[Karel_van_Mander|Mander]] as ''\u2018a beautiful temple, with the perspective very well done\u2019''.<br>\n\nUsually, Pourbus draws his inspiration for the Italian renaissance style from contemporary graphics such as those by D\u00fcrer, Raphael, and Titian. For example, he drew strongly on Titian for the middle panel of the Damhouder Triptych at the Church of Our Lady in Bruges, for which he also designed a frame entirely in line with the renaissance style.<br>\n\nAs a well-established painter, Pourbus is occasionally seen as too expensive during this period. <br>\nFor example, in autumn of 1571, he creates a design for an altarpiece for the Church of Our Lady in Damme, but a different, cheaper painter, Jacob van den Coornhuuse, is commissioned to do the work instead. <br>\n[[File:The Lamentation by Pieter Jansz. Pourbus.JPG|thumb|450px|Pieter Jansz. Pourbus. ''Lamentation''. [http://schorrcollection.org.uk Schorr Collection]. ]]\nEven so, Pourbus\u2019 studio continues to run smoothly throughout the 1570s. Among others, he works in close collaboration with [[Antoon_Claeissens|Antonius Claeissens]], who utilises Pourbus\u2019 style more than anyone else in Bruges in the early years of his career. <br>\nThe monumental piece \"Lamentation\" from the Schorr collection, one of the highlights of the exposition at Museum Gouda in 2018, is the result of intensive collaboration between the two.<br>\n\n===== Darker years =====\nIn 1578, a military force comes knocking on the city gates of Bruges. <br>\nThere is little resistance to the invading force. Just like Ghent before it, Bruges becomes a Calvinist republic. The city that barely felt the torrent of the Iconoclastic Fury in 1566 is unable to escape the stranglehold of the Eighty Years\u2019 War. <br>\nOnce the threat of war increases after the Pacification of Ghent fails, the city\u2019s magistrate repeatedly asks the Pourbus for his advice on building the city\u2019s defenses. His knowledge of water management, for instance, can be of use in flooding certain areas as a defensive manoeuvre.37<br>\nEven after the change in power that follows the city\u2019s capture in 1578, Pourbus continues to serve the now Protestant city authorities and enjoys the confidence of the magistrate. For example, he is appointed district head of his district in the Sint-Nicolaas-Zestendeel in December 1580. This may indicate that he converted\nto Calvinism, like his son. After all, the switch from Catholicism to Calvinism in Bruges means that Pourbus\nbecomes intimately entwined in the Protestant network.<br>\nHe had already painted the portraits of various prominent Protestants in previous years, such as the wartime mayor Jan Wyts and Calvinist leaders such as Pieter Dominicle.\nPourbus barely has time for painting during these years.<br>\n[[File:Zeghere van Male Pierter Pourbus 1578.jpg|thumb|350px|Pieter Pourbus''Zeghere van Male'', 1578]]\nHis epitaph for the Catholic Zeger van Male probably dates back to 1578, before the invasion by Ghent Protestants. During this period, Pourbus is mainly active as a water management expert and engineer.\nIn 1580, he paints a peculiar plan of the Abbey of the Dunes that was intended to serve as a guide for the\nreconstruction of the monastic complex after the war.\nApparently, he has enough credibility within the suppressed Catholic community left to be granted this commission. On the other hand, in autumn of that same year, he also creates the designs for the deconsecrated\nChurch of St Christopher (the site for which he painted the fishmongers\u2019 altar with his son only four years previ- ously) to be turned into a market hall, because it was no longer permitted to be used for worship.<br>\n\nPieter Pourbus dies in January of 1584.<br>\n\nHe may have been one of the many victims of the plague that strikes Bruges at the time. His widow, Anna Blondeel, is allocated a pension by both the city\u2019s magistrate and the Liberty of Bruges. Pourbus\u2019 memory is honored in many different ways. His portrait is hung in the guildhall as a memento to him.42<br>\n\n== Founding Father of a painting dynasty ==\nPourbus\u2019 oeuvre is often referred to as the swan song of the old Bruges school of painting. <br>\nAt the same time, he was also a notorious innovator. In terms of art history, he was the leading figure of his generation in Bruges.<br>\nHe is an all-round artist that practises his art in every register, from very simple matters to providing the\nLiberty\u2019s water authority with strategic advice.<br>\nStylistically speaking, he is part of the generation of [[Frans_Floris|Frans Floris]], the generation that realized the breakthrough of the Italian Renaissance in the Low Countries. The Joyous Entry of Charles V and prince Philip II, which dates from 1549, is a testament to that.<br>\n\nIt marks the perfect occasion for introducing the public to radical new innovations. As such, Pourbus manages\nto make a name for himself during his lifetime as one of the most important painters of his generation, both\nin Bruges and elsewhere; for example, Italian contem- poraries such as historian [[Lodovico Guicciardini|Ludovico Guicciardini]] and\nartist biographer [[Giorgio Vasari]] make mention of him.<br>\nPourbus develops a very recognizable hand, characterized by classicist restraint, with a restrained style that is dominated primarily by clear lines. <br>\nWhile comparing his artistic personality to contemporaries such as Maarten de Vos and Pieter Brueghel the Elder may force one to put his talent into a wider perspective, he is unmatched\nas a portraitist. <br>\nHe continues to surprise on that front throughout his entire career, both with individual\nportraits and group depictions. This sets him apart as an extraordinary visual chronicler of the eventful\nhistory of sixteenth-century Bruges.\nPourbus\u2019 influence on his immediate surroundings\npersists.43 <br>\nAs mentor to his son and grandson, [[Frans_Pourbus_the_Elder|Frans the Elder]] and [[Frans_Pourbus_the_Younger|Frans the Younger]], he gains international renown.<br>\nAs such, Pourbus is the founding father of an artistic lineage that will set the tone in the field of portraiture for three generations, until the arrival of the baroque portrait supersedes them.\n\n==Works==\n\nThe [[Groeningemuseum]] in Bruges displays many of his works.  <br>\nThe [https://www.museumgouda.nl/nl Gouda Museum] possesses also works by the artist. <br>\nThe Sint Janskerk and the [[Church of Our Lady, Bruges]] have some of his art on display.\n\n<gallery heights=\"225px\" widths=\"170px\">\nFile:Pieter Pourbus Portrait of Gentleman.jpg|''Portrait of a gentleman in armour'', [[Mus\u00e9e de Picardie]], France\nFile:Pieter Pourbus Christian van der Goes.jpg|''Portrait of [[Christian van der Goes]]'', 1574\nFile:Pieter Pourbus Portret1.jpg|''Portrait of Jan van Eyewerve'', 1551, [[Groeningemuseum]], Bruges\nFile:Pieter Pourbus Portret2.jpg|''Portrait of Jacquemyne Buuck'', 1551, [[Groeningemuseum]], Bruges\nFile:Pierre Pourbus - Bearded, red-headed Man, seated - Google Art Project.jpg|''Bearded, red-headed man, seated'', 1555\nFile:Pieter_Pourbus_._Portrait_of_a_young_lady.1554.signed_and_dated.jpg |''Portrait of a young noble lady'', Signed and dated 1554,  Private Collection\nFile:Laatste Avondmaal, 1548, [[Groeningemuseum]], 0040033000.jpg|''The last supper'', 1548,  Groeningemuseum, Bruges\nFile:Brugge Pieter Pourbus (1523-1584) - Het Laatste Avondmaal (1562) 9-03-2010 16-16-12kopie.jpg|thumb|''The Last Supper'', 1562, [[Church of Our Lady, Bruges\nFile:Pieter Pourbus - Allegory of true love.jpg|''Allegory of true love'', c.1547, [[Wallace Collection]]\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Publications ==\n# Paul Huvenne, ''Pierre Pourbus, peintre brugeois, 1524-1584,'' cat. exp., Mus\u00e9e Memling (H\u00f4pital Saint-Jean), 29 juin-30 septembre 1984, Bruges, Cr\u00e9dit Communal, 1984.\n# Paul Philippot, ''La Peinture dans les anciens Pays-Bas xve\u2009\u2013\u2009xvie si\u00e8cles'', Paris, Flammarion, 1994, 303 p., ({{ISBN|978-2-08010-937-8}}), p. 230-231.\n# Maryan W. Ainsworth, Win Blockmans, Till-Holger Borchert (et al.), ''Bruges et la Renaissance. De Memling \u00e0 Pourbus'', cat. expo., Bruges, 15 ao\u00fbt-6 d\u00e9cembre 1998 Gand, Ludion ; Paris, Flammarion ; Bruges, Stichting Kunstboek, 1998, 319 p., ({{ISBN|90-5544-232-1}}).\n# Irene Smets, ''Le Mus\u00e9e Groeninge \u00e0 Bruges : un choix des plus belles \u0153uvres'', Ludion, 2000, 127 p. ({{ISBN|978-9-05544-257-7}}).\n# (nl) Anne Van Oosterwijk, Maarten Bassens, Till-Holger Borchert, Heidi Deneweth, Brecht Dewilde (et al.), ''Vergeten Meesters, Pieter Pourbus en de Brugse schilderkunst van 1525 tot 1625'', \u00e9d. : SNOECK GENT. Catalogue of the exposition at the Groeningen Museum, Bruges Oct.13, 2017 - Jan.21, 2018. 336 pages.\n# (en) Anne Van Oosterwijk (et al.), ''The forgotten masters. Pieter Pourbus and Bruges painting from 1525 to 1625'', \u00e9d. : SNOECK GENT. Catalogue de l'exposition au mus\u00e9e Groeningen de Bruges Oct.13 2017 - Jan.21 2018. 336 pages.\n# (en) (nl) Marc De Beyer et Josephina De Fauw, ''Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda'', 2018. Catalogue of the  exhibition Feb. 17 - June 17 2108 in Museum Gouda. 86 pages.\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Pieter Pourbus}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pourbus, Pieter}}\n[[Category:Flemish painters]]\n[[Category:Flemish Renaissance painters]]\n[[Category:Dutch Renaissance painters]]\n[[Category:1523 births]]\n[[Category:1584 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Bruges Guild of Saint Luke]]\n[[Category:People from Gouda, South Holland]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{copyedit|date=March 2020}}\n'''Pieter Jansz. Pourbus''' (c. 1523, in [[Gouda, South Holland|Gouda]] \u2013 30 January 1584, in [[Bruges]]) was a [[Dutch and Flemish Renaissance painting|Flemish Renaissance painter]], draftsman, engineer and cartographer who was active in Bruges during the 16th century.  He is known primarily for his religious and portrait painting.<ref name=RKD>.[https://rkd.nl/en/explore/artists/64551 Pieter Pourbus] at the [[Netherlands Institute for Art History]] {{in lang|nl}}</ref>\n[[File:The Annunciation, by Pieter Pourbus.jpg|thumb|450px|''The Annunciation'',1552, Museum Gouda, Netherlands, oil on panel, 117 x 112 cm, signed c.: 1552 / PETRVS POVRBUS ME FECIT]]\n\n== Life ==\n=== Birth and origin ===\nPieter Pourbus was born in Gouda in 1523 or 1524.  He moved to Bruges at the age of 20.<br>\n\nVery little is known on his childhood and youth, at the time when he lived in Gouda. <br>\nAll sources only make a brief mention of his origins.<br>\n\n===== Gouda =====\nHis first biography was written by contemporary artist biographer [[Karel_van_Mander|Karel van Mander]] in his renowned \"Painting Book\" (\"Schilder-boeck\") of 1604<ref>Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''\"Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda\"'', 2018. Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda. 86 pages. Article written by Paul H.A.M. Abels, \u00a7.1, page 31</ref>.<br>\n\"Even so, I would not like to conceal any of the most special. That is why I wish to present this view of\nPieter Pourbus\". <br>\n\"Born in the Dutch town of Gouda, he based himself in Bruges from an early age\".<ref>Van Mander 1604, fol. 257r; original text in Dutch:''\u2018\u2026Evenwel soud\u2019 ick niet geern eenige der besonderste verzwijgen. Daerom ick hier wil voor ooghen stellen Pieter Pourbus.\u2019''</ref> <br>\nWith these words, [[Karel_van_Mander|Karel van Mander]], the author of the 1604 work \"Het Schilder-Boeck, over t\u2019 leven der Vermaerde Doorluchtighe Schilders\" (\"The Book of Painters, about the life of Renowned Honourable Painters\") describes his colleague from Bruges.<br>\nKarel remembers him as \"the painter of Bruges\".<br>\nThe two met in 1580, when [[Karel_van_Mander|Van Mander]] fled the ravages of the Eighty Years\u2019 War and stayed in Bruges for a time. <br>\nPourbus must have overwhelmed him with information about all of the beautiful sights of Bruges at that time, as he was the source for most of the information [[Karel_van_Mander|Van Mander]] provides regarding the Bruges school of painting.<ref>Article written by Paul Huvenne, \u00a7.1 page 9, in Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''\"Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda\"'', 2018. Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda. 86 pages</ref><br>\n\nWe do not have any portrait or self portrait of Pieter Pourbus, but he probably included his own portrait on the left altar wing of the \"Tryptych of the Holy Sacrament fraternity\" in the St Saviour's Cathedral, Bruges.<br>\n\nAt the time, Pourbus was not considered a native in Bruges itself.\nWhen he registers as a master painter with the guild of Sculptors and Saddlers in 1543 as \"Pieter Jansyns Poerbus\", he is explicitly marked \"as a stranger\" (\u2018vrymde\u2019) in the records. He must have been 19 or 20 years old at the time, based on the mentions of his age in a range of documents. From there, we can conclude that he must have been born in 1523 or 1524. <br>\n\nAt the occasion of the exhibition on Pieter Pourbus at the Gouda Museum in 2018, Paul Abels wrote in the catalogue of this exhibition on the role Gouda played in his life by putting what little is known about his ties to the city in the context of late-medieval religious and social life In Gouda.<ref>Article written by Paul H.A.M. Abels, \u00a7.1, page 31, in Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''\"Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda\"'', 2018. Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda. 86 pages</ref>\n\nHe mentioned that the name Pourbus features several times in Gouda at the start of the sixteenth century. <br>\nBut he adds that only one person in the Gouda city archives who would actually qualify as Pourbus\u2019 father, namely \"Jan Pieterssoen Puerboss\", who features in the city accounts in 1529. The accounts mention a payment made to him for \"painting the board that stands in front of the window\". The mention is brief, but it allows to corroborate [[Karel_van_Mander|Van Mander\u2019s]] claim about Pourbus\u2019 Gouda roots by another contemporary source. <br>\nThis source also shows that he was also a painter, although it is not possible to know what his real artistic skills were. The mention most likely refers to painting a (town\u2019s) coat of arms on a shutter.<ref>Paul H.A.M. Abels, \u00a7. page 31, in Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda'', 2018. Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda. 86 pages</ref>\n\n===== From Gouda to Bruges =====\nPourbus\u2019 move to Bruges can be explained because Bruges is known to be a city that produces excellent painting, although that reputation is waning slightly when Pourbus arrives.<br>\nBruges is familiar territory for the Gouda residents. Pourbus will have heard many stories about the city of Bruges when growing up. The two cities are closely connected by the beer trade, which was the leading line of business in Gouda at the time.<br>\n\nBefore he went to Bruges, he may have studied his craft with Utrecht-based painters such as [[Jan_van_Scorel|Jan van Scorel]] or the Leiden masters. Recent technical research suggests Leiden, more so than Utrecht.<br>\n[[Lucas_van_Leyden|Lucas van Leyden]] and [[Cornelis_Engebrechtsz.|Cornelis Engelbrechtsz]] pass away when Pourbus is still a child, but he may have come into contact with Engelbrechtsz\u2019s three sons, [[Cornelis Cornelisz Kunst|Cornelis]], [[Lucas Cornelisz de Kock|Lucas]], and [[Pieter Cornelisz. Kunst]], who followed in their father\u2019s footsteps and became painters in their own right.<br>\n\n=== Pourbus in Bruges ===\nShortly after he registers with the \u2019Sculptors and Saddlers\u2019 Guild in Bruges in 1543 ( the Bruges \"[[Guild_of_Saint_Luke|Guild of Saint Luke]]\"), Pieter Pourbus marries. He weds Anna, the youngest daughter of painter [[Lancelot_Blondeel|Lancelot Blondeel]]. His marriage to the daughter of an established artist lacking any male heirs is very important for his reputation and further career as a master painter.<ref>from the article written by Paul H.A.M. Abels, \u00a7. page 34, in: Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''\"Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda\"'', 2018. Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda. 86 pages</ref> <br>\nIn 1545 or 1546, she bears him a son, Frans ([[Frans_Pourbus_the_Elder|\u2018the elder\u2019]]), who is predestined to take up his father\u2019s brush after him. Pourbus integrates into the city of Bruges with ease. <br>\nHe becomes a member of the crossbowmen\u2019s guild of St George and often visits the rhetorician meetings organised by the Chamber of the Holy Spirit. [[Lancelot_Blondeel|Blondeel]], who is a well-respected person there, may have introduced him.<br>\nIt is unclear where Pourbus\u2019 initial training as a painter took place. Recent research into his underdrawings\npoints in the direction of Leiden.6 Very few concrete details of his first few years in Bruges are known. It would appear that he initially operated from under the wing of his successful father-in-law.<ref>Paul Huvenne, in Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda: Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''\"Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda\"'', 2018.  86 pages. \u00a7.1 page 11</ref>\n===== Working in Blondeel's studio =====\n[[Lancelot_Blondeel|Blondeel]], perhaps the most authoritative artist of his generation in Bruges, introduced an early form of Italian renaissance painting.<br>\n[[File:Pieter Pourbus - Last Supper - WGA18255.jpg|thumb|right|350px|Pieter Pourbus - ''The last Supper'', 1548 - 46,5x63cm - [[Groeningemuseum]], Bruges]]\nPourbus\u2019 earliest work is in line with this school of painting. \nIn fact, it remains unclear in some cases whether the works are the result of collaboration or whether they were painted by him individually, for instance in the case of ''\"The Seven Joys of the Virgin\"'', which hangs in the Tournai Cathedral, for which these two artists join forces.<br>\n\nPourbus\u2019 smaller work ''\"Last Supper\"''<ref>Pourbus made later five other depictions of the Last Supper (all of imposing size) in addition to the present painting, including the 1559 Triptych of the Brotherhood of the Sacrament (Saint James Church, Bruges) and that of 1562 in the Onze Lieve Vrouwekerk, Bruges. <br>\nThe former still retains its original double-sided wings, the left one showing Melchisedech\u2019s Offering and the right one, Elijah Fed by the Angel, </ref> indicates that his father-in-law also introduced him to the ''\u2018Rederijker\u2019'' or rhetorician circles of amateur poets and reciting artists.<br>\n\nThis little painting depicts the Last Supper as described in the Refrains of rhetorician [https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eduard_de_Dene Edward van Dene].<br>\n\nNote on this small painting a rare iconography for this subject, with the presence of a devil entering the room on the right of the painting.\n\n[[File:Pierre pourbus-triptico de los santos juanes-prado.jpg|thumb|center|750px|Pieter Pourbus - Triptych of '' \"Baptism of Christ\" '', 1549, 241x377cm - [[Prado Museum]], Madrid]]<br>\n\nIt is unclear exactly when Pourbus began working for himself. <br>\nFor example, he began painting for the Spanish art market at an early stage. <br>\nHis monumental triptych ''\"The Baptism of Christ\"'', which dates back to 1549 and now hangs in the Museo del Prado in Madrid, indicates how grand these commissions can be.<br>\n\nOne of his works was recently unearthed, the Spanish epitaph of Martin Cruzat, which dates back to 1548. <br>\nThis is a classic Piet\u00e0 featuring the deceased\u2019s portrait, evidently intended for the grave in his parish church in Pamplona. <br>\nThe piece was on display for the public for the first time at the exhibition of the Museum Gouda in 2018.<br>\n\nAnother work that dates back to Pourbus\u2019 early years in Bruges is his only remaining non-religious history work, ''\"An Allegory of True Love\"'', currently part of the Wallace Collection in London. <br>\n[[File:Pieter Pourbus - Allegory of true love.jpg|thumb|550px|center| Pieter Pourbus - ''Allegory of true love'', c. 1547 - 132,8x205,7cm - Wallace collection, London]]This painting shows Pourbus\u2019s painting style as truly innovative.<ref>Paul Huvenne, in Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda: Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda'', 2018. 86 pages. \u00a7.2 page 11</ref><br>\n\n===== Out of Blondeel's shadow =====\n[[File:Pieter Pourbus Portret1.jpg|thumb|200px|Pieter Pourbus ''Portrait of Jan van Eyewerve'', 1551 - [[Groeningemuseum]], Bruges]] [[File:Pieter Pourbus Portret2.jpg|thumb|200px|Pieter Pourbus ''Portrait of Jacquemyne Buuck'', 1551, [[Groeningemuseum]], Bruges]]As from 1549, Pourbus leaves his father-in-law\u2019s shadow. From this moment on, his name starts appearing in all sorts of historical documents with great frequency. <br>\nHe is named yearly, and sometimes even daily, in many official sources. <br>\nSome notable commissions will also have played a role in increasing his fame, such as the decorations for the Joyous entry of Charles V and prince Philip II in 1549 (\u2018Blijde intocht van Karel V en prins Filips in 1549\u2019), a design for a new banquet hall, and a ''\"Last Judgment\"'' (''\u2018Laatste Oordeel\u2019''); all of these are commissions for the so-called ''\u2018Brugse Vrije\u2019'' (also known as the Liberty of Bruges), the legally autonomous territory of Bruges.<br>\n\nAnother prominent commission was his works for the mausoleum of Margaret of Austria at the Annunciation Convent in Bruges, which the magnificent Annunciation currently displayed at Museum Gouda was part of.\nPourbus gradually became the preferred master painter of the bourgeoisie, such as wine merchant Jan van Eyewerve and his wife Jacquemyne Buuck. They had their portraits painted to celebrate their wedding. <br>\n\nThe fact that Pourbus expressly dates and signs his works throughout this period is indicative of the rise in his confidence.<br>\n\n\nPourbus also made many topographic maps. <br>\nHe began using a new methodology based on triangulation that resulted in very modern-looking maps.13 It was a new format for visual reports intended to support surveyors\u2019 legal reports. <br>\nIt is unknown how Pourbus obtained this knowledge, but his 1549 map of the canal between Damme and Sluis indicates that he was most likely already using the new technique at that time, constituting a grand innovative move in 1540s Bruges.<br>\nAll of this hard work paid off: in 1552, Pourbus bought Huis Rome (\u2018the Rome House\u2019) on the Heer Jan Admiraelstraat. [[Karel_van_Mander|Van Mander]] later writes that here, Pourbus set up the best painting studio he ever saw.<ref>Paul Huvenne, in Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda: Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda'', 2018. 86 pages. \u00a7.2 page 13</ref>\n\n===== Active Guild member =====\nAs from 1551, Pourbus became a prominent and active member of his guild\u2019s council; he served two terms as dean of the guild and five terms as sworn elder. He was very committed to his guild duties; for example, as an elder, he participated in quality checks on fellow guild members. He visited Simon Puseel in response to the latter\u2019s poor performance in gilding the dome of the Jerusalem Chapel in Bruges. As a dean, he acted to prevent paintings from Dordrecht being sold inside the city walls. He also defended the guild\u2019s interests several times in the leasing of land it owned in the province of Zeeland. Clearly, Pourbus was a very active and committed member of the Bruges Guild of Sculptors and Saddlers.<ref>Paul Huvenne, in Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda: Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda'', 2018. 86 pages. \u00a7.2 page 16</ref>\n\n=== Pourbus\u2019 best years ===\nThe decade following his breakthrough in 1550 boasts the best work of his career.<br>\n\n===== Pourbus truly surpasses himself as a portraitist =====\nPourbus\u2019 fine portrait of Joris (?) van den Heede, whose family motto \"sint sine dentes sales\" (\"be witty without spite\") was taken word for word from Erasmus\u2019 introduction to \"In Praise of Folly\", is reminiscent of that of Jan van Eyewerve.\n\nAnd with his portraits of \"Pieter Dominicle and his wife Livina van der Beke\", Pourbus truly surpasses himself as a portraitist.<br>\n[[File:Pieter Pourbus . Portrait of a young lady.1554.signed and dated.jpg|thumb|275px|Pieter Pourbus.''Portrait of a noble young lady''.signed and dated 1554.<br>\nPrivate collection]]\nThe captivating elegance with which he portrays women is even more evident in this smaller \"Portrait of a noble young lady\", from a private collection.<br>\nUnfortunately, no inscription or family crest is to be seen on the painting, neither could it be found after IR or X rays examination. It is therefore impossible to identify the lady depicted, but her rich dress, distinguished appearance, and self-aware gaze shows that this is a lady of considerable standing.<br>\nHer dress, with its delicate lace collar, allowed [http://vlaamseprimitieven.vlaamsekunstcollectie.be/en/research/researchers/paul-huvenne Paul Huvenne]<ref>https://www.codart.nl/museums/kmska-director-paul-huvenne-to-retire-on-1-august/</ref>, who discovered this painting, to date the portrait as having been painted before 1560.<br>\nAnd indeed the IR examination revealed Pourbus' monogram, as well as the year when he painted this captivating portrait: 1554.<br>\nAs [http://vlaamseprimitieven.vlaamsekunstcollectie.be/en/research/researchers/paul-huvenne Paul Huvenne]<ref>https://www.codart.nl/museums/kmska-director-paul-huvenne-to-retire-on-1-august/</ref> writes it, it is one of the finest example of Pourbus\u2019 portrait style, and probably the masterwork among its intimate portraits:<br>\n\"He manages to lift the striking likeness that is expected of any portrait to an icon that radiates societal and spiritual values. In doing so, he endows the person depicted with a detached, but animated beauty that leaves no one unmoved\"<ref>Paul Huvenne, in Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda: Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda'', 2018. 86 pages. \u00a7.3 page 16 and 17</ref>.<br>\nIn an article published at the occasion of the exhibition at the Gouda Museum, another author describes this portrait as [https://marccouwenbergh.nl/de-mona-lisa-van-pieter-pourbus-meester-schilder-uit-gouda/ '''the Mona Lisa of Pourbus\"'']. <br>\nMoreover, in a detailed following article<ref>https://marccouwenbergh.nl/anna-van-bueren-versus-de-mona-lisa-van-pieter-pourbus-meester-schilder-uit-gouda/</ref>, he draws attention on many similarities between this portrait and the portrait of [[Anna van Egmont]], first wife of [[William the Silent|William of Orange]], belonging to the Royal collection, The Hague. The comparison can also be found [[Anna_van_Egmont#A_newly_discovered_portrait_of_Anna_van_Egmont?|here]].<br>\n\nHis art as a portraitist is also revealed during this decade by group portraits that are second to none. <br>\nThe wing-panels with portraits of the Members of the Noble Confraternity of the Holy Blood and the Sacra Confrerie of St Salvators is a wonderful example. <br>\nThe position of the sitters suggest that Pourbus must have envisioned the work of Utrecht-based painter [[Jan_van_Scorel|Jan van Scorel]].<br>\n\n===== History painter  =====\nPourbus is now also able to prove himself as a history painter.<br>\n\nHe follows up on his impressive Last Judgment, now part of the Groeningemuseum\u2019s collection, and the beautiful Annunciation in Museum Gouda with the smaller Crucifixion in 1557.<br>\n[[File:Pourbus-Vanbelle-Triptiek.jpg|thumb|left|500px|Pourbus - ''\"Van Belle Triptych\"'',1556 - St James' church, Bruges]]\nBut more than any other work, the Van Belle triptych illustrates how Pourbus\u2019 style has matured.<br>\nIn many ways, this triptych is a key piece in his oeuvre, not only because it is one of his best paintings, but also because it is so well documented in archival materials.\nFor example, one of the items that survived is the original design drawing that Pourbus presented to Joos Van Belle for his approval.<br>\nThe sheet bears handwritten comments, in which the artist agrees to portray the Madonna not with clenched hands but in a more resigned posture: ''\u2018with the arms pressed crosswise over one another\u2019''. The theme of Our Lady of the Seven Sorrows on the middle panel was a very popular one in Pourbus\u2019 day, and it will have been quite a challenge for the artist to come up with a new, convincing composition to depict the theme.\nPourbus\u2019 depiction of the Virgin Mary owes much to the statue of the Madonna with Child by Michelangelo at the Church of Our Lady in Bruges.<br>\n\nThe success that is now due to Pourbus is confirmed by his 1558 Piet\u00e0 at the \u00c9glise Saint-Maurice in Annecy and\nhis Adoration of the Golden Calf, painted around 1559, currently in show at the National Gallery in Dublin.<br>\n\nPourbus becomes the leading representative of the Italian High Renaissance as propagated in Antwerp by [[Frans_Floris|Frans Floris]]. This is a stylistic idiom that is completely contrary to the deep-seated gothic tradition. \nOne example of this high renaissance style is the grotesques in which he depicts the portraits of Mr and Mrs Ghuyse-Van Male.<br>\nAt this point, Pourbus\u2019 work features more translucent, confident brushwork and a clear composition style that manages to reconcile tradition and innovation. These aspects are readily apparent in the Van Belle triptych, in which he paraphrases the composition of Jan van Eyck\u2019s [[Virgin_and_Child_with_Canon_van_der_Paele|\"The Virgin and Child with Canon Van der Paele\"]] from 1436, which is now part of the collection at the Groeningemuseum in Bruges.<br>\nWith his innovation of the style, Pourbus makes his mark on the artistic production in Bruges and the surrounding area. As such, the Italian [[Lodovico_Guicciardini|Ludovico Guicciardini]] names him as one of the most important painters of his time in his ''\"Descrittione di tutti i Paesi Bassi\"'' or ''\"Description of all the Low Countries\"'' in 1567.<ref>Paul Huvenne, in Catalogue of the exhibition Feb.17 - June 17 2108 at Museum Gouda: Marc De Beyer & Josephina De Fauw, ''\"Pieter Pourbus, Master painter of Gouda\"'', 2018.  86 pages. page 16 to 20</ref>\n\n===== The leading painter in Bruges =====\n[[File:Portrait of a woman with unknown coat of arms, 1565 -National Galleries of Scotland, ,Edinburg.jpg|thumb |Pieter Pourbus - ''Portrait of a woman with unknown coat of arms'', 1565 - [https://www.nationalgalleries.org National Galleries of Scotland], Edinburg]]\nLancelot Blondeel passes away in 1561.<br>\n\nPourbus is now the leading painter in Bruges.<br>\n\nIn the years that follow, he teaches many an apprentice, including his son Frans, and [[Antoon_Claeissens|Antonius Claeissens]], who starts working for him at one point.<br>\n\nBusiness is going well, but artistically speaking, Pourbus appears to stagnate somewhat during this period.\nSeveral altar pieces that date from this period are a far cry from his best work. <br>\n\nHowever, he does show his skills as an exquisite portraitist from time to time, such as in this Portrait of a twenty-six years old woman from Edinburg. <br>\n\nIn spite of the coat of arms, this young lady has not yet been identified. It has been suggested that she might be part of the De Grave family, who are originally from Flanders but settled in Andalusia.\nIf so, this would once again be a nod to the Spanish presence in Bruges at the time.<br>\n\nThe portrait displays such immense refinement and grace that it was taken to be a portrait of Mary Stuart, Queen of Scots for much of the nineteenth century. <br>\n\nWith his smooth, enamel-like stylisation, Pourbus has imbued the woman\u2019s face with an introverted and enigmatic quality. <br>\nIt is reminiscent of [[Lodovico_Guicciardini|Guicciardini\u2019s]] assertions that in Bruges, ''\u2018the women are as beautiful, lovely, modest and temperate as in any city in these lands\u2019''.<br>\n\n[[File:Pieter Pourbus - Portrait of Jan Lopez Gallo and His Three Sons - WGA18256.jpg|thumb|left|Pieter Pourbus - ''Portrait of Jan Lopez Gallo and His Three Sons'', 1568 - [https://www.museabrugge.be/en/visit-our-museums/our-museums-and-monuments/groeningemuseum Groeningen Museum], Bruges]]\n[[File:Francois Van der Straeten.jpg|thumb|450pix|Pieter Pourbus - ''Portrait de Francois Van der Straeten'', 1567 - [https://www.museummayervandenbergh.be/en Mayer Van Den Bergh Museum], Anvers]]\n\nIn 1567, Pourbus produces yet another portrait, of Knight Fran\u00e7ois van der Straten. <br>\n\nHe draws inspiration from an allegorical print by Cornelis Theunisz from 1537 in which a child, an hourglass, and a skull remind one of the transience of life in much the same way.<br>\n\nVan der Straten was a leading authority in the Liberty of Bruges and an academically trained lawyer. <br>\n\nThe text that he points out on the note beneath his hand reads as follows: \"COGNITIO DEI ET NATVRAE RATIONANIS\" (''\"Knowledge of God and the Reasonable Nature\"'').<br>\nThis is a reference to his humanist view of life.<br>\nHis motto, \"ABSIT GLORIA\" (\"reject glory\"), once again brings to mind the notion of vanitas.<br>\n\nIn the same year, he also paints the portrait of Pieter de Corte, the freshly appointed bishop of the recently created bishopric of Bruges. <br>\nDe Corte was appointed by King Philip II of Spain. Considering the prestige involved in this commission, it was naturally granted to Pourbus.<br>\n\nHis Portrait of Juan Lopez Gallo and his sons, dating back to 1568, once again prove that the ties with his Spanish clientele had not weakened in the slightest.<br>\nHis work can even be found on the Canary Islands. There, Pourbus dealt with his clients\u2019 differing customs in a very special way, by adjusting the size of his retables to suit the size of altar that was customary in Spain at the time.<br>\nSometimes, he leaves the actual execution of paintings for his more distant clients to atelier staff, as shown in his \"Mount at Calvary\", presently in the Cathedral of San Pedro in Soria.<br>\n\n===== The year of the great map =====\nHis most important commission of the 1560s is the monumental Map of the Liberty of Bruges [fi g. 14]. <br>\nThe accounts allow us to trace Pourbus\u2019 steps almost on a daily basis during the many days he spends on this work. The documents tell us all about how he adapted existing materials or created new ones, who worked on the map with him, who came along with him (such as lawyers, surveyors, and magistrates), and how he repeatedly presented his progress to the client. He completed this magnum opus in 1571.<br>\n\n=== From 1570 to Pourbus death ===\n===== The 1570's =====\nAfter the enormous effort of the Great Map, it seems Pourbus had more time for regular commissions once\nagain. <br>\nHis students have since left his studio. His son [[Frans_Pourbus_the_Elder|Frans]] left for Antwerp in 1569 to make his fortune as a painter there, and [[Antonius Claeissens]] became the official city painter of Bruges in 1570. <br>\nPourbus continues to paint portraits without a moment\u2019s rest.[[File:Pieter Pourbus - Portrait of Olivier van Nieulant - WGA18257.jpg|thumb|left| Pieter Pourbus - ''Portrait of Olivier van Nieulant'', 1573 - 49,5 \u00d7 37,5 cm, <br>[https://www.kmska.be/en Museum of Fine Arts], Antwerp]]\nHis style does change slightly, as evidenced by his portrait of Olivier Nieulant dated 1573, which is now in the Royal Museum of Fine Arts Antwerp.\n\nHis brushwork becomes less transparent and more enamel-like. This shift is also apparent in his history paintings, such as the Altarpiece of St Hubert in the collection of Museum Gouda.\nThe shift lends a cooler appearance, a more classicist quality to his work, but also makes it slightly more rigid.<br>\n\nIt is remarkable how well Pourbus is able to focus his compositions or inventions on the Italian renaissance\nidiom, considering the fact that he never went to Italy.\nA good example of this, once again, is the Altarpiece of St Hubert, painted before 1572, which is praised by [[Karel_van_Mander|Mander]] as ''\u2018a beautiful temple, with the perspective very well done\u2019''.<br>\n\nUsually, Pourbus draws his inspiration for the Italian renaissance style from contemporary graphics such as those by D\u00fcrer, Raphael, and Titian. For example, he drew strongly on Titian for the middle panel of the Damhouder Triptych at the Church of Our Lady in Bruges, for which he also designed a frame entirely in line with the renaissance style.<br>\n\nAs a well-established painter, Pourbus is occasionally seen as too expensive during this period. <br>\nFor example, in autumn of 1571, he creates a design for an altarpiece for the Church of Our Lady in Damme, but a different, cheaper painter, Jacob van den Coornhuuse, is commissioned to do the work instead. <br>\n[[File:The Lamentation by Pieter Jansz. Pourbus.JPG|thumb|450px|Pieter Jansz. Pourbus. ''Lamentation''. [http://schorrcollection.org.uk Schorr Collection]. ]]\nEven so, Pourbus\u2019 studio continues to run smoothly throughout the 1570s. Among others, he works in close collaboration with [[Antoon_Claeissens|Antonius Claeissens]], who utilises Pourbus\u2019 style more than anyone else in Bruges in the early years of his career. <br>\nThe monumental piece \"Lamentation\" from the Schorr collection, one of the highlights of the exposition at Museum Gouda in 2018, is the result of intensive collaboration between the two.<br>\n\n===== Darker years =====\nIn 1578, a military force comes knocking on the city gates of Bruges. <br>\nThere is little resistance to the invading force. Just like Ghent before it, Bruges becomes a Calvinist republic. The city that barely felt the torrent of the Iconoclastic Fury in 1566 is unable to escape the stranglehold of the Eighty Years\u2019 War. <br>\nOnce the threat of war increases after the Pacification of Ghent fails, the city\u2019s magistrate repeatedly asks the Pourbus for his advice on building the city\u2019s defenses. His knowledge of water management, for instance, can be of use in flooding certain areas as a defensive manoeuvre.37<br>\nEven after the change in power that follows the city\u2019s capture in 1578, Pourbus continues to serve the now Protestant city authorities and enjoys the confidence of the magistrate. For example, he is appointed district head of his district in the Sint-Nicolaas-Zestendeel in December 1580. This may indicate that he converted\nto Calvinism, like his son. After all, the switch from Catholicism to Calvinism in Bruges means that Pourbus\nbecomes intimately entwined in the Protestant network.<br>\nHe had already painted the portraits of various prominent Protestants in previous years, such as the wartime mayor Jan Wyts and Calvinist leaders such as Pieter Dominicle.\nPourbus barely has time for painting during these years.<br>\n[[File:Zeghere van Male Pierter Pourbus 1578.jpg|thumb|350px|Pieter Pourbus''Zeghere van Male'', 1578]]\nHis epitaph for the Catholic Zeger van Male probably dates back to 1578, before the invasion by Ghent Protestants. During this period, Pourbus is mainly active as a water management expert and engineer.\nIn 1580, he paints a peculiar plan of the Abbey of the Dunes that was intended to serve as a guide for the\nreconstruction of the monastic complex after the war.\nApparently, he has enough credibility within the suppressed Catholic community left to be granted this commission. On the other hand, in autumn of that same year, he also creates the designs for the deconsecrated\nChurch of St Christopher (the site for which he painted the fishmongers\u2019 altar with his son only four years previ- ously) to be turned into a market hall, because it was no longer permitted to be used for worship.<br>\n\nPieter Pourbus dies in January of 1584.<br>\n\nHe may have been one of the many victims of the plague that strikes Bruges at the time. His widow, Anna Blondeel, is allocated a pension by both the city\u2019s magistrate and the Liberty of Bruges. Pourbus\u2019 memory is honored in many different ways. His portrait is hung in the guildhall as a memento to him.42<br>\n\n== Founding Father of a painting dynasty ==\nPourbus\u2019 oeuvre is often referred to as the swan song of the old Bruges school of painting. <br>\nAt the same time, he was also a notorious innovator. In terms of art history, he was the leading figure of his generation in Bruges.<br>\nHe is an all-round artist that practises his art in every register, from very simple matters to providing the\nLiberty\u2019s water authority with strategic advice.<br>\nStylistically speaking, he is part of the generation of [[Frans_Floris|Frans Floris]], the generation that realized the breakthrough of the Italian Renaissance in the Low Countries. The Joyous Entry of Charles V and prince Philip II, which dates from 1549, is a testament to that.<br>\n\nIt marks the perfect occasion for introducing the public to radical new innovations. As such, Pourbus manages\nto make a name for himself during his lifetime as one of the most important painters of his generation, both\nin Bruges and elsewhere; for example, Italian contem- poraries such as historian [[Lodovico Guicciardini|Ludovico Guicciardini]] and\nartist biographer [[Giorgio Vasari]] make mention of him.<br>\nPourbus develops a very recognizable hand, characterized by classicist restraint, with a restrained style that is dominated primarily by clear lines. <br>\nWhile comparing his artistic personality to contemporaries such as Maarten de Vos and Pieter Brueghel the Elder may force one to put his talent into a wider perspective, he is unmatched\nas a portraitist. <br>\nHe continues to surprise on that front throughout his entire career, both with individual\nportraits and group depictions. This sets him apart as an extraordinary visual chronicler of the eventful\nhistory of sixteenth-century Bruges.\nPourbus\u2019 influence on his immediate surroundings\npersists.43 <br>\nAs mentor to his son and grandson, [[Frans_Pourbus_the_Elder|Frans the Elder]] and [[Frans_Pourbus_the_Younger|Frans the Younger]], he gains international renown.<br>\nAs such, Pourbus is the founding father of an artistic lineage that will set the tone in the field of portraiture for three generations, until the arrival of the baroque portrait supersedes them.\n\n==Works==\n\nThe [[Groeningemuseum]] in Bruges displays many of his works.  <br>\nThe [https://www.museumgouda.nl/nl Gouda Museum] possesses also works by the artist. <br>\nThe Sint Janskerk and the [[Church of Our Lady, Bruges]] have some of his art on display.\n\n<gallery heights=\"225px\" widths=\"170px\">\nFile:Pieter Pourbus Portrait of Gentleman.jpg|''Portrait of a gentleman in armour'', [[Mus\u00e9e de Picardie]], France\nFile:Pieter Pourbus Christian van der Goes.jpg|''Portrait of [[Christian van der Goes]]'', 1574\nFile:Pieter Pourbus Portret1.jpg|''Portrait of Jan van Eyewerve'', 1551, [[Groeningemuseum]], Bruges\nFile:Pieter Pourbus Portret2.jpg|''Portrait of Jacquemyne Buuck'', 1551, [[Groeningemuseum]], Bruges\nFile:Pierre Pourbus - Bearded, red-headed Man, seated - Google Art Project.jpg|''Bearded, red-headed man, seated'', 1555\nFile:Pieter_Pourbus_._Portrait_of_a_young_lady.1554.signed_and_dated.jpg |''Portrait of a young noble lady'', Signed and dated 1554,  Private Collection\nFile:Laatste Avondmaal, 1548, [[Groeningemuseum]], 0040033000.jpg|''The last supper'', 1548,  Groeningemuseum, Bruges\nFile:Brugge Pieter Pourbus (1523-1584) - Het Laatste Avondmaal (1562) 9-03-2010 16-16-12kopie.jpg|thumb|''The Last Supper'', 1562, [[Church of Our Lady, Bruges\nFile:Pieter Pourbus - Allegory of true love.jpg|''Allegory of true love'', c.1547, [[Wallace Collection]]\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Publications ==\n# Paul Huvenne, ''Pierre Pourbus, peintre brugeois, 1524-1584,'' cat. exp., Mus\u00e9e Memling (H\u00f4pital